WEBVTT

00:14.959 --> 00:17.000
[bright tone]

00:17.083 --> 00:19.959
[mellow music]

00:20.041 --> 00:28.125
♪  ♪

00:43.125 --> 00:51.166
♪  ♪

01:03.458 --> 01:05.583
[car horn honks twice]

01:06.959 --> 01:10.166
woman: I've got nothing to do
with committee appointments.

01:10.250 --> 01:12.542
Let her submit
a proposal to Anna.

01:12.625 --> 01:16.000
- She's here in
Philadelphia.

01:16.083 --> 01:19.375
All she wants
is half an hour.

01:19.458 --> 01:22.208
She's a bright girl--
Swarthmore,

01:22.291 --> 01:24.166
and a doctorate from Penn.

01:24.250 --> 01:25.625
Her family has money.

01:25.709 --> 01:28.083
Carrie, are you listening?
- Yep.

01:28.166 --> 01:31.250
- She wants to lobby
for a constitutional amendment.

01:31.333 --> 01:34.750
- Oh, she thinks Congress is
going to suddenly roll over?

01:34.834 --> 01:36.500
I thought you said
she was bright.

01:36.583 --> 01:38.166
Paula who?

01:38.250 --> 01:40.000
- Paul, Alice Paul.

01:40.083 --> 01:41.417
She worked in England.

01:41.500 --> 01:43.500
- Don't bring me
any radicals, Harriot.

01:43.583 --> 01:47.000
- She's not a radical.
She's a Quaker.

01:47.083 --> 01:48.083
She came all the way
down here

01:48.166 --> 01:50.625
to meet you and Anna.
Be nice.

01:50.709 --> 01:53.667
[energetic music]

01:53.750 --> 02:01.875
♪  ♪

02:16.625 --> 02:18.041
- It's mine.

02:18.125 --> 02:19.542
- Saw it first.

02:21.458 --> 02:23.000
- It's calling my name.

02:23.083 --> 02:24.709
- I must be deaf.

02:24.792 --> 02:28.166
♪  ♪

02:28.250 --> 02:30.041
Heads.

02:35.208 --> 02:36.959
It's not your style.

02:37.041 --> 02:39.333
- Nice try.

02:41.166 --> 02:43.959
- Carrie Catt's very proud
of the state-by-state campaign.

02:44.041 --> 02:45.208
Congratulate her.
- On what?

02:45.291 --> 02:46.542
64 years of begging,

02:46.625 --> 02:48.208
and now women can
vote in nine states.

02:48.291 --> 02:49.542
How many years
per state is that?

02:49.625 --> 02:51.000
You congratulate her.

02:51.083 --> 02:52.375
- We waltz in there
and say, "Do the math,"

02:52.458 --> 02:54.583
we won't get the letterhead
or the office.

02:54.667 --> 02:56.208
You want to be two girls
on a corner soap box,

02:56.291 --> 02:57.500
or do you want
to go to Washington

02:57.583 --> 02:59.333
and play with the big lads?

02:59.417 --> 03:02.792
I want them to give us
the congressional committee.

03:04.291 --> 03:05.041
- What?

03:05.125 --> 03:06.709
- Did you swallow it whole?

03:06.792 --> 03:08.333
- I strangled it first.

03:08.417 --> 03:09.750
Carrie: The president

03:09.834 --> 03:13.667
of the National American Woman
Suffrage Association,

03:13.750 --> 03:15.875
the reverend
Anna Howard Shaw.

03:15.959 --> 03:19.875
[applause]

03:26.000 --> 03:27.709
- Don't bring up suffrage
in England.

03:27.792 --> 03:29.709
Shaw thinks the Brits
are hooligans.

03:29.792 --> 03:31.709
No matter what, don't get
your knickers in a knot.

03:31.792 --> 03:33.208
Don't start up.
Be polite.

03:33.291 --> 03:35.959
- I'm always polite.
When am I not polite?

03:36.041 --> 03:38.959
- It's the color,
with your hair.

03:42.291 --> 03:44.375
- The passage of
a constitutional amendment

03:44.458 --> 03:46.542
is not a realistic goal.

03:46.625 --> 03:47.709
- It could become one.

03:47.792 --> 03:50.125
- Theoretically, yes,
in the future.

03:50.208 --> 03:51.583
First, we need more states.

03:51.667 --> 03:52.875
- Susan B. Anthony
petitioned for it

03:52.959 --> 03:54.667
in 1868 and again in 18--

03:54.750 --> 03:56.083
- Thank you for
the history lesson.

03:56.166 --> 03:57.375
- If Susan B. Anthony
were alive today,

03:57.458 --> 04:00.125
she'd say 1912
is the future.

04:00.208 --> 04:02.041
- Dr. Shaw and I worked
side by side

04:02.125 --> 04:04.208
with Susan
and Elizabeth Stanton

04:04.291 --> 04:06.542
while you were still
in diapers, Miss Paul.

04:06.625 --> 04:08.083
Would you do me a favor
and please refrain

04:08.166 --> 04:11.166
from second-guessing her
thoughts on this topic?

04:11.250 --> 04:13.542
- "Do me a favor.
Don't second-guess

04:13.625 --> 04:15.083
"Susan's thoughts
on cheese.

04:15.166 --> 04:17.166
"We worked side by side
with Susan.

04:17.250 --> 04:18.500
"We worked cheek to cheek
with Susan.

04:18.583 --> 04:21.125
She despised cheddar
and she loathed muenster."

04:21.208 --> 04:22.291
[giggles]

04:22.375 --> 04:24.250
Carrie:
A constitutional amendment

04:24.333 --> 04:25.709
that gives women
the right to vote,

04:25.792 --> 04:27.458
assuming it doesn't
die in committee,

04:27.542 --> 04:29.959
will almost certainly
be vetoed in the Senate.

04:30.041 --> 04:31.500
We waste time,
we waste money.

04:31.583 --> 04:33.250
We squander the goodwill
of the Democrats

04:33.333 --> 04:36.542
and worse, we look like babies
with no political savvy.

04:36.625 --> 04:38.667
Which gives ammunition
to our opponents.

04:38.750 --> 04:41.917
Have you any other
thoughts, Miss Paul?

04:42.000 --> 04:43.458
- A parade.

04:43.542 --> 04:45.000
In March.

04:45.083 --> 04:48.041
The day Wilson's arriving
for his inauguration.

04:48.125 --> 04:50.959
We're guaranteed a crowd,
and hopefully,

04:51.041 --> 04:54.291
some badly needed-publicity
from the newspapers.

04:54.375 --> 04:58.291
- Mrs. Blatch tells me
that you two met in England.

04:58.375 --> 05:00.875
Those women give suffrage
a bad name.

05:00.959 --> 05:02.417
- Better than
no name at all.

05:02.500 --> 05:04.458
- I beg your pardon?

05:04.542 --> 05:07.625
- Lucy was studying
at Oxford.

05:07.709 --> 05:09.125
- What?
I was.

05:09.208 --> 05:11.375
- While I'm in sympathy
with the British suffragettes,

05:11.458 --> 05:13.333
I don't approve
of their methodology.

05:13.417 --> 05:16.792
We don't throw bricks
to make our position clear.

05:16.875 --> 05:19.417
If I send you to Washington,

05:19.500 --> 05:22.792
I want your assurance that there
will be no hooligan tactics.

05:22.875 --> 05:24.458
- You have it.

05:24.542 --> 05:26.250
I don't consider myself
above the law

05:26.333 --> 05:28.417
under any circumstances.

05:34.875 --> 05:38.041
- Then you may take over NAWSA's
committee in Washington.

05:38.125 --> 05:41.583
Have your parade,
Miss Paul.

05:42.875 --> 05:44.166
- Thank you.

05:44.250 --> 05:47.667
- You'll have to raise
your own funds, of course.

05:47.750 --> 05:51.542
- [quiet snoring]

05:51.625 --> 05:59.750
♪  ♪

06:19.625 --> 06:22.166
man: That the female mind
is inferior to the male mind

06:22.250 --> 06:23.458
need not be assumed.

06:23.542 --> 06:25.333
man: There is
something about...

06:25.417 --> 06:27.375
man: There is something about
it essentially different...

06:27.458 --> 06:30.250
man: And that this difference
is of a kind and degree

06:30.333 --> 06:31.667
that with votes for women

06:31.750 --> 06:33.792
would constitute
a political danger

06:33.875 --> 06:36.166
ought to be plain
to everyone.

06:36.250 --> 06:37.959
man: I do not wish to see
the day come

06:38.041 --> 06:40.375
when the women in my state
shall trail their skirts

06:40.458 --> 06:42.875
in the muck and mire
of partisan politics.

06:42.959 --> 06:46.208
- These flippant girls
singing "votes for women"

06:46.291 --> 06:48.875
know not the disasters
they invite

06:48.959 --> 06:51.291
by this reckless movement.

06:51.375 --> 06:59.375
♪  ♪

06:59.458 --> 07:01.875
- Flip you for it.

07:17.750 --> 07:19.250
- Oh, my.
- Let me see.

07:19.333 --> 07:21.208
Let me see.
- What? Hey!

07:27.750 --> 07:30.500
[light suspenseful music]

07:30.583 --> 07:38.667
♪ ♪

07:48.458 --> 07:50.375
[switch clicking]

08:11.333 --> 08:14.083
- How do you raise money
to raise money?

08:14.166 --> 08:15.417
- Oh, excuse me.
- All right.

08:15.500 --> 08:18.250
- All we need is a handful
of society women.

08:18.333 --> 08:20.041
I found someone who
designs parade floats.

08:20.125 --> 08:22.333
- Floats? I thought we were
gonna keep it small.

08:22.417 --> 08:23.667
- Why?

08:23.750 --> 08:25.333
- Because you've never
organized a parade before.

08:25.417 --> 08:27.291
Neither have I--it's not like
giving a dinner party.

08:27.375 --> 08:29.792
- Have you ever given
a dinner party?

08:29.875 --> 08:30.834
- No.

08:30.917 --> 08:32.291
- Then what are you
worried about?

08:32.375 --> 08:33.833
Did you get the permit?

08:33.917 --> 08:35.500
- I've been to the district
police three times this week.

08:35.582 --> 08:39.833
- Go over his head.
To the parks commissioner.

08:39.917 --> 08:42.207
- I could go under his belt.

08:42.291 --> 08:44.000
- I bet you would.
- [giggles]

08:44.082 --> 08:47.500
[steam whooshing]
[background chatter]

08:47.583 --> 08:51.375
[machines clattering]

08:55.000 --> 08:56.875
Lucy: I think
a thousand women marching

08:56.959 --> 09:00.291
means more than 10,000
signatures on a piece of paper.

09:00.375 --> 09:02.166
Suffrage is not a dead issue.

09:02.250 --> 09:03.375
It's us, it's you.

09:03.458 --> 09:05.250
It's living,
breathing women.

09:05.333 --> 09:06.542
We're not just a petition

09:06.625 --> 09:08.959
that can be crumbled up
and tossed away.

09:09.041 --> 09:10.834
And this is what
marching does.

09:10.917 --> 09:12.959
Marching shows the politicians
that we women

09:13.041 --> 09:15.375
are united in our demand
for political--

09:15.458 --> 09:18.000
- Show me a raise!
Screw the politicians!

09:18.083 --> 09:19.041
[laughter]

09:19.125 --> 09:20.542
- Go ahead, if you think
it'll help.

09:20.625 --> 09:23.041
[crowd murmuring]
Now, there's--

09:23.125 --> 09:26.875
- 146 women burned to death
in a factory fire last month.

09:26.959 --> 09:28.375
Where's your fire escape?

09:28.458 --> 09:30.875
[Lucy continues in background]

09:30.959 --> 09:33.041
Laws are made
by elected officials.

09:33.125 --> 09:35.792
A fire escape can be
required by law.

09:35.875 --> 09:37.583
A vote is a fire escape.

09:37.667 --> 09:40.375
- We take Sunday off
to la-dee-dah for you,

09:40.458 --> 09:41.542
we get fired on Monday.

09:41.625 --> 09:43.000
You have children, Missus?

09:43.083 --> 09:44.917
They don't eat ballots.

09:45.000 --> 09:46.750
Alice: Go ahead,
shout your head off.

09:46.834 --> 09:48.458
The ruling class
are those who have a voice,

09:48.542 --> 09:49.792
and that voice is a vote.

09:49.875 --> 09:51.208
No one hears you.

09:51.291 --> 09:53.333
- Fttt!

09:53.417 --> 09:54.750
- Votes for women.

09:54.834 --> 09:57.959
- The parade's gonna happen
and, uh...please.

09:58.041 --> 10:00.208
Please,
would you like one?

10:00.291 --> 10:02.583
The more the merrier.

10:02.667 --> 10:04.291
Anyone.

10:09.709 --> 10:12.709
- [speaking in
foreign language]

10:12.792 --> 10:15.250
A vote is a fire escape.

10:15.333 --> 10:17.583
A vote is fire escape!

10:17.667 --> 10:19.250
[speaking foreign language]

10:19.333 --> 10:21.875
- That's right, a vote--
a vote's a fire escape.

10:21.959 --> 10:26.875
♪  ♪

10:26.959 --> 10:30.959
Mrs. Wenclawska...Ruza.

10:31.041 --> 10:32.792
- Alice Paul.

10:32.875 --> 10:36.166
- Now give me the rest,
college girl.

10:39.166 --> 10:42.667
- Helen Keller's in town.
Arrange for me to meet her.

10:45.709 --> 10:48.750
[phone ringing]

10:53.208 --> 10:54.959
Alice: I don't know
which hotel.

10:55.041 --> 10:56.208
She's deaf and blind.

10:56.291 --> 10:59.083
If she found it,
I'm sure you can.

10:59.166 --> 11:01.625
- Hi, Mabel Vernon.

11:01.709 --> 11:03.792
I played hockey with
Alice at Swarthmore.

11:03.875 --> 11:05.500
- Lucy Burns.

11:05.583 --> 11:07.625
D.C. police will not
guarantee our safety

11:07.709 --> 11:10.750
if we march on the third,
because Wilson's arriving.

11:10.834 --> 11:12.083
- We're not
changing the date.

11:12.166 --> 11:14.125
- Exactly what I said.
I like that one.

11:14.208 --> 11:17.667
And he said, "Well--"
[clears phlegm, snorts]

11:17.750 --> 11:19.917
"Miss, there might be trouble
with inaugural crowds

11:20.000 --> 11:23.291
and I'm afraid I won't be
held responsible."

11:23.375 --> 11:24.500
And I said, "Look, Mister,

11:24.583 --> 11:26.291
we're entitled to
police protection."

11:26.375 --> 11:29.500
And he said, "Why don't you
take my advice, you ladies?

11:29.583 --> 11:31.250
Why don't you just
stay at home?"

11:31.333 --> 11:32.500
- Miss Paul?

11:32.583 --> 11:36.625
Ida Wells-Barnett
from the Chicago delegation.

11:41.208 --> 11:43.834
I'm told you
expect Negro women

11:43.917 --> 11:46.667
to march in a separate unit,
at the back.

11:46.750 --> 11:48.750
- Southern suffrage groups
threaten to withdraw--

11:48.834 --> 11:51.959
- Are the ladies afraid
we'll march out of step?

11:52.041 --> 11:53.166
Call their bluff.

11:53.250 --> 11:55.041
- We can't afford
to lose their support.

11:55.125 --> 11:56.709
Not with the Democrats
in office.

11:56.792 --> 11:58.667
- Who's "we"?
Women?

11:58.750 --> 12:00.500
Or just white women?

12:00.583 --> 12:02.041
- Now, wait a minute.

12:02.125 --> 12:04.542
- We have one agenda: suffrage.
Add another issue--

12:04.625 --> 12:06.375
- If we don't
stand up now,

12:06.458 --> 12:09.458
what happens to Negro women
when you finally get the vote?

12:09.542 --> 12:11.792
They'll keep us out of the
polling place any way they can.

12:11.875 --> 12:13.750
- Other colored groups have
agreed to the compromise.

12:13.834 --> 12:15.375
- Not perfect,
but we got to be practical.

12:15.458 --> 12:19.041
- Dress up prejudice
and call it politics?

12:19.125 --> 12:22.208
I expected more
from a Quaker.

12:22.291 --> 12:25.458
I'll march with my peers
or not at all.

12:26.792 --> 12:29.333
- I understand.

12:35.750 --> 12:39.083
[bluesy music]

12:39.166 --> 12:43.041
woman: ♪ Oh, baby,
you are so fine ♪

12:43.125 --> 12:48.000
♪ I want to sip you up
like wine ♪

12:48.083 --> 12:51.959
♪ Oh, baby,
you are so sweet ♪

12:52.041 --> 12:54.458
♪ You're knock, knock,
knocking me ♪

12:54.542 --> 12:57.583
♪ Up off of my feet ♪

12:57.667 --> 13:05.417
♪  ♪

13:05.500 --> 13:06.917
- How are you, ma'am?

13:07.000 --> 13:09.250
Doris Stevens, National
Woman Suffrage Association.

13:09.333 --> 13:10.583
We're short
on volunteers today,

13:10.667 --> 13:11.583
if you have an hour
to spare?

13:11.667 --> 13:14.125
- No, no, I can't,
not today.

13:14.208 --> 13:16.375
- Or if you'd like
to make a contribution.

13:16.458 --> 13:17.917
- No, thank you!

13:18.000 --> 13:20.291
[bicycle bell rings]

13:20.375 --> 13:22.125
- Watch out sweetheart,
hot soup.

13:22.208 --> 13:23.291
- Jenny!

13:23.375 --> 13:24.792
- How are you, ma'am?

13:24.875 --> 13:26.792
I'm Doris Stevens, National
Woman Suffrage Association.

13:26.875 --> 13:28.709
We're short on
volunteers today,

13:28.792 --> 13:29.792
if you have
an hour to spare.

13:29.875 --> 13:31.250
- I'm sorry, I can't.

13:31.333 --> 13:35.125
- Or if you'd like
to make a pledge.

13:35.208 --> 13:36.792
- Another time perhaps.

13:36.875 --> 13:39.375
- Come along, Jenny,
mind the wet.

13:39.458 --> 13:41.625
- Jenny, come on,
take my hand.

13:41.709 --> 13:43.125
- How are you, ma'am?

13:43.208 --> 13:46.291
Doris Stevens, National Woman
Suffrage Association.

13:46.375 --> 13:51.375
♪  ♪

13:51.458 --> 13:54.375
[energetic tune]

13:54.458 --> 14:02.583
♪ ♪

14:08.333 --> 14:12.208
- ♪ Oh, baby,
you are sublime ♪

14:12.291 --> 14:16.500
♪ I want to slurp you up
like wine ♪

14:16.583 --> 14:20.208
♪ Oh baby,
you are so sweet ♪

14:20.291 --> 14:22.500
♪ You knock, knock,
knock me ♪

14:22.583 --> 14:24.834
♪ Off my feet ♪

14:24.917 --> 14:28.500
♪ If you got me rollin' ♪

14:28.583 --> 14:32.750
♪ I'd like to take you
by the hand ♪

14:32.834 --> 14:38.083
♪  ♪

14:38.166 --> 14:39.458
- Hmm.

14:39.542 --> 14:43.458
♪ ♪

14:43.542 --> 14:45.208
- We're going to solicit
donations.

14:45.291 --> 14:47.667
Let's look
like we need them.

14:49.500 --> 14:52.417
[chamber orchestra plays]

14:52.500 --> 14:56.709
♪ ♪

14:56.792 --> 14:58.709
- I could tell
you were from Wyoming.

14:58.792 --> 15:00.166
That's my favorite state.

15:00.250 --> 15:02.959
They gave women the vote
from the get-go.

15:04.125 --> 15:06.417
- What a beautiful dog
you're wearing.

15:06.500 --> 15:09.083
Didn't we meet at
Mrs. Bellwood's lunch?

15:09.166 --> 15:10.834
- Yes.
- I'm Doris Stevens,

15:10.917 --> 15:12.667
National
Woman Suffrage Association...

15:12.750 --> 15:14.333
- So nice to meet you.

15:17.291 --> 15:19.250
- By the politicians,
by the newspapers.

15:19.333 --> 15:21.583
It's very important
to raise awareness.

15:21.667 --> 15:23.500
- Yes, ah, Senator Leighton,
good to see you.

15:23.583 --> 15:25.500
- Good to see you.
Yes, of course.

15:25.583 --> 15:27.542
- Good evening,
Senator.

15:30.625 --> 15:32.250
- Hi, John,
nice to see you.

15:32.333 --> 15:33.375
- Senator.

15:33.458 --> 15:36.250
[indistinct chatter continues]

15:36.333 --> 15:44.458
♪ ♪

15:45.875 --> 15:48.792
- Mmm, it's beautiful,
isn't it?

15:48.875 --> 15:50.750
- Yes.
- I'm sorry, I'm Lucy Burns.

15:50.834 --> 15:52.750
- Emily Leighton.

15:52.834 --> 15:54.667
- Oh, gosh. Yes.

15:54.750 --> 15:57.500
I'm actually part of NAWSA's
congressional committee.

15:57.583 --> 15:59.417
National American Woman
Suffrage Association.

15:59.500 --> 16:01.000
- Ah.

16:01.083 --> 16:05.041
- We're giving a parade.
Have you heard about our parade?

16:05.125 --> 16:08.291
- I really don't follow
politics, Miss Burns.

16:08.375 --> 16:10.750
I haven't the head for it.
[chuckles]

16:12.166 --> 16:13.583
- We're citizens
or we're chattel.

16:13.667 --> 16:15.333
You don't really need
a degree from Harvard

16:15.417 --> 16:17.166
to figure that out.

16:17.250 --> 16:18.875
- Would you excuse us?

16:18.959 --> 16:20.792
- Oh, Senator Leighton,
it was very--

16:20.875 --> 16:23.458
nice to meet you.

16:23.542 --> 16:25.792
[laughter]

16:25.875 --> 16:27.625
woman: Muller vs. Oregon,
1908.

16:27.709 --> 16:31.000
Judge rules in favor of shorter
working hours for women.

16:31.083 --> 16:32.625
Then, goes on record saying

16:32.709 --> 16:35.083
healthy mothers serve
the public interest.

16:35.166 --> 16:37.542
- So, that was a victory.
And as your old labor lawyer,

16:37.625 --> 16:38.792
are you not?
- I am.

16:38.875 --> 16:40.125
- Those women
were being exploited.

16:40.208 --> 16:41.667
- Sure, now they're
being patronized.

16:41.750 --> 16:43.792
We're not broodmares.

16:43.875 --> 16:47.041
[laughter]

16:48.750 --> 16:50.208
- Thank you--ah!

16:51.125 --> 16:52.667
Labor law
with a sexual bias

16:52.750 --> 16:54.166
will come back
and bite us in the ass.

16:54.250 --> 16:56.333
- The issue isn't opportunity.
It's protection.

16:56.417 --> 16:59.583
Women need protection.
- We all need protection.

16:59.667 --> 17:01.417
But when women complain,
people call it hysteria

17:01.500 --> 17:03.166
and then they rush
to fetch the doctor.

17:03.250 --> 17:04.916
- As long as women accept
protective law

17:05.000 --> 17:06.916
they can't expect equality.

17:07.000 --> 17:09.583
They need full citizenship.

17:09.666 --> 17:11.583
- Ben Weissman.

17:11.666 --> 17:14.165
- Alice Paul.

17:14.250 --> 17:16.165
- Inez Milholland.

17:16.250 --> 17:18.000
- I'm hungry.

17:18.083 --> 17:19.959
Have you eaten?

17:22.583 --> 17:25.625
[upbeat jazz music plays]

17:25.709 --> 17:28.500
♪ ♪

17:28.583 --> 17:31.041
A stout old maid
with facial hair.

17:31.125 --> 17:32.542
Carrie Nation
waving her axe,

17:32.625 --> 17:34.333
that's what people think of
when you say suffragist.

17:34.417 --> 17:36.542
Lucy: So NAWSA fights it with
"Madonna and child".

17:36.625 --> 17:38.750
- Women who nurture the family,
rock the baby,

17:38.834 --> 17:40.625
serve the dinner,
serve society.

17:40.709 --> 17:43.208
Serving, serving, serving.
- Always.

17:43.291 --> 17:46.542
- But the new suffragist is
single, young, independent...

17:46.625 --> 17:47.500
- Educated.

17:47.583 --> 17:48.792
- And very, very beautiful.

17:48.875 --> 17:50.542
Lucy: She's you.

17:50.625 --> 17:51.667
- On a horse.

17:51.750 --> 17:52.583
- A cowgirl?

17:52.667 --> 17:54.041
- A warrior.
- A herald.

17:54.125 --> 17:55.917
- Joan of Arc
with 10,000 women

17:56.000 --> 17:57.250
following her down
Pennsylvania Avenue!

17:57.333 --> 17:59.709
- An ideal woman who can
lead us up the mountain.

17:59.792 --> 18:01.208
- Mm-hmm,
or off a cliff.

18:01.291 --> 18:02.458
- No.
- No!

18:02.542 --> 18:05.041
- Something like this?

18:08.083 --> 18:11.333
- Oh, hey, you could
do this for a living.

18:11.417 --> 18:12.583
- You think so?

18:12.667 --> 18:14.333
[laughter]
- He does.

18:14.417 --> 18:16.500
What's the name of that
miserable rag you work for?

18:16.583 --> 18:18.333
Oh, yeah,
"The Washington Post."

18:30.417 --> 18:31.792
- That's exactly
what I want.

18:31.875 --> 18:33.917
- Have dinner with me tomorrow.

18:34.000 --> 18:36.917
When I do business with men,
we have dinner.

18:37.000 --> 18:38.166
Don't you want
equal treatment?

18:38.250 --> 18:39.500
- I'm having dinner
with Helen Keller.

18:39.583 --> 18:41.667
- Oh, don't stare,
she hates that.

18:41.750 --> 18:43.000
[both laugh]

18:43.083 --> 18:44.834
Have lunch with me.

18:44.917 --> 18:46.792
- I'd like to meet some
"Washington Post" reporters.

18:46.875 --> 18:48.291
- After lunch.
- Before.

18:48.375 --> 18:51.333
- Don't you trust me?
- I don't know you.

18:51.417 --> 18:53.125
- Would you like to?

18:53.208 --> 18:55.875
Well, see, Negro men have been
voting since the Civil War.

18:55.959 --> 18:57.959
You think the ballot's
changed his life?

18:58.041 --> 18:59.709
It's a cash and carry
country.

18:59.792 --> 19:01.792
What's the vote
gonna buy you?

19:01.875 --> 19:03.375
- Self-respect,
for starters.

19:03.458 --> 19:05.792
- I vote and I have
no self-respect.

19:05.875 --> 19:07.959
What do you think women
are gonna do when they vote?

19:08.041 --> 19:09.166
Reform politics?

19:09.250 --> 19:11.291
- Because
we're morally superior?

19:11.375 --> 19:13.125
That's a nice fairy tale.

19:13.208 --> 19:14.542
I don't have any illusions
about women.

19:14.625 --> 19:16.375
There's good and bad,
just like men.

19:16.458 --> 19:18.917
I don't know what they're
gonna do with their vote,

19:19.000 --> 19:20.625
and I don't care.

19:20.709 --> 19:23.333
- Prohibition?
Legalize birth control?

19:23.417 --> 19:24.709
- It doesn't matter.

19:24.792 --> 19:26.542
That's not the point.
- What's the point?

19:26.625 --> 19:28.000
- We're legitimate citizens.

19:28.083 --> 19:29.792
We're taxed without
representation,

19:29.875 --> 19:31.166
we're not allowed
to serve on juries,

19:31.250 --> 19:32.834
so we're not tried
by our peers.

19:32.917 --> 19:34.166
It's unconscionable,

19:34.250 --> 19:36.333
not to mention
unconstitutional.

19:36.417 --> 19:37.500
We don't make the laws

19:37.583 --> 19:39.625
but we have to obey them,
like children.

19:39.709 --> 19:40.959
You know the
suffrage amendment

19:41.041 --> 19:43.500
has only once been voted on
in the senate?

19:43.583 --> 19:45.667
But we've got nine states now.

19:45.750 --> 19:47.834
That's 4 million women voters,

19:47.917 --> 19:49.959
which means
1/5th of the House,

19:50.041 --> 19:51.125
1/6th of the Senate

19:51.208 --> 19:53.333
and 1/7th
of the electoral votes

19:53.417 --> 19:55.000
come from suffrage states.

19:55.083 --> 19:58.083
You want to know what women
can buy with that?

19:58.166 --> 20:01.375
- Were you the smartest girl
in your class?

20:01.458 --> 20:04.208
- No. In the whole school.

20:04.291 --> 20:05.834
- Ahh.

20:05.917 --> 20:07.166
Would you be talking to me

20:07.250 --> 20:10.000
if I didn't work for
"The Washington Post"?

20:11.375 --> 20:13.750
- No.
- Mm-hmm.

20:13.834 --> 20:16.000
Have lunch with me,
Alice Paul.

20:33.875 --> 20:38.125
- This desk
was Susan B. Anthony's.

20:38.208 --> 20:41.083
From the old headquarters.

20:41.166 --> 20:43.500
[whispering]
It was in storage.

20:45.125 --> 20:46.542
It's haunted.

20:46.625 --> 20:47.834
- [huffs]

20:50.000 --> 20:51.625
Did you kiss him?

20:51.709 --> 20:54.083
'Cause if you don't
want him, I'll take him.

20:54.166 --> 20:55.959
- Shh.

20:58.333 --> 20:59.542
Listen.

21:01.083 --> 21:04.959
- Ask her how we'll get
the amendment on the floor.

21:10.500 --> 21:12.250
What does she say?

21:12.333 --> 21:14.709
- She says...

21:14.792 --> 21:17.458
just do it.

21:17.542 --> 21:20.458
[dramatic music]

21:20.542 --> 21:23.792
♪  ♪

21:23.875 --> 21:26.875
["Everything is Everything"
by Lauryn Hill]

21:26.959 --> 21:28.000
♪  ♪

21:28.083 --> 21:29.917
[Hill vocalizing]

21:30.000 --> 21:32.500
♪ ♪

21:32.583 --> 21:34.709
[vocalizing]

21:34.792 --> 21:36.458
♪ ♪

21:36.542 --> 21:39.959
[vocalizing]

21:40.041 --> 21:43.250
[crowd cheering]

21:43.333 --> 21:45.041
♪ ♪

21:45.125 --> 21:47.792
Hill: ♪ Everything,
everything ♪

21:47.875 --> 21:49.542
♪ Is everything
is everything ♪

21:49.625 --> 21:52.583
♪ What is meant to be
will be ♪

21:52.667 --> 21:55.458
[cheers and applause]

21:55.542 --> 21:57.583
♪ After winter,
after winter ♪

21:57.667 --> 22:00.208
♪ Must come spring,
must come spring ♪

22:00.291 --> 22:01.291
♪ Change ♪

22:01.375 --> 22:02.792
♪ It comes eventually ♪

22:02.875 --> 22:05.125
♪  ♪

22:05.208 --> 22:09.625
♪ Everything is everything ♪

22:09.709 --> 22:12.291
♪ What is meant to be will be ♪

22:12.375 --> 22:15.458
[cheers and applause]

22:15.542 --> 22:18.500
[marching band plays]

22:18.583 --> 22:26.750
♪ ♪

22:38.792 --> 22:46.917
♪ ♪

22:48.583 --> 22:50.834
♪ Must come spring ♪

22:50.917 --> 22:53.583
♪ Change, it comes
eventually ♪

22:53.667 --> 22:56.083
♪  ♪

22:56.166 --> 22:58.458
♪ Everything, everything ♪

22:58.542 --> 23:01.208
♪ Is everything ♪

23:01.291 --> 23:09.417
♪  ♪

23:24.458 --> 23:27.208
- Hey hey hey hey!
Hey, girlie girls, girls!

23:27.291 --> 23:29.041
Over here!
[whistles]

23:29.125 --> 23:30.875
Get over here, come on!

23:30.959 --> 23:33.500
Get off the streets.
Go home to your mother!

23:33.583 --> 23:35.333
- My mother is here!

23:35.417 --> 23:37.500
[men laughing]

23:38.750 --> 23:41.959
- If you was my wife,
I'd bash your head in!

23:42.041 --> 23:44.959
[booing]

23:45.041 --> 23:51.333
♪  ♪

23:57.458 --> 24:00.208
man: Welcome, Mr. President!

24:00.291 --> 24:01.375
man: Welcome, sir!

24:01.458 --> 24:02.792
- Welcome to Washington,
Mr. President.

24:02.875 --> 24:06.750
Design Commissioner Stevenson.
Right this way.

24:06.834 --> 24:09.417
- I thought there
would be a big crowd.

24:09.500 --> 24:11.166
Where is everybody?

24:11.250 --> 24:14.291
[haunting female soprano]

24:14.375 --> 24:18.542
♪  ♪

24:18.625 --> 24:20.125
- Hey, you, he-shes,

24:20.208 --> 24:23.583
get off the streets
and go home, you hussies!

24:23.667 --> 24:24.875
You wanna be a man?

24:24.959 --> 24:28.667
- Who wears the pants
in your family?

24:28.750 --> 24:30.750
- What you got
under your skirt?

24:30.834 --> 24:38.709
♪  ♪

24:42.000 --> 24:43.458
- Go back home!

24:43.542 --> 24:46.041
- Men built this country
and made it what it was today!

24:46.125 --> 24:52.792
♪ ♪

24:52.875 --> 24:56.709
[crowd shouting]

25:01.667 --> 25:05.792
[overlapping shouting]

25:15.917 --> 25:17.333
- Mom!

25:17.417 --> 25:19.583
Mom!

25:19.667 --> 25:22.834
[music continues]

25:22.917 --> 25:30.333
♪ ♪

25:30.417 --> 25:31.917
[horse whinnies]

25:32.000 --> 25:33.792
- Officer!

25:37.583 --> 25:40.625
Officer!
Over here!

25:40.709 --> 25:42.333
Over here!

25:42.417 --> 25:50.625
♪  ♪

26:04.250 --> 26:10.917
♪  ♪

26:12.458 --> 26:15.458
[knocking on door]

26:16.875 --> 26:21.750
- When's the last time suffrage
was on the front page?

26:21.834 --> 26:24.208
"Nation aroused by
open insults to women.

26:24.291 --> 26:26.417
Cause wins
popular sympathy."

26:26.500 --> 26:28.583
Oh, look, another photograph
of you, warrior princess,

26:28.667 --> 26:30.750
above the fold,
thank you.

26:30.834 --> 26:33.500
- Alice, you were right
about the wings.

26:34.917 --> 26:37.583
"Even those who are opposed
to giving women the vote

26:37.667 --> 26:39.208
"must now admit
that the movement

26:39.291 --> 26:40.709
is no ephemeral thing."

26:40.792 --> 26:43.792
- "The Evening Star"
blames the D.C. Police.

26:43.875 --> 26:47.625
- So does "The Post."
My feet hurt.

26:47.709 --> 26:48.834
- We got lucky.

26:48.917 --> 26:50.333
- A hundred people
in the hospital.

26:50.417 --> 26:52.041
You call that lucky,
Miss Paul?

26:52.125 --> 26:55.041
- Uh, she means
the extra publicity.

26:55.125 --> 26:56.250
Look, Anna.

26:56.333 --> 26:57.667
- The police
were negligent.

26:57.750 --> 27:00.959
"The Post" is calling
for an investigation.

27:01.041 --> 27:02.625
Wilson's a gentleman
from the South.

27:02.709 --> 27:04.792
I don't see how he can deny
a delegation of women,

27:04.875 --> 27:06.917
especially when they were
practically molested

27:07.041 --> 27:08.291
at his doorstep.

27:08.375 --> 27:09.625
- A delegation?

27:09.709 --> 27:11.667
- Before the bruises fade.

27:11.750 --> 27:13.250
- Before he addresses
Congress.

27:13.333 --> 27:15.917
- He's the president of
the United States, Miss Paul.

27:16.000 --> 27:18.375
You don't exactly
go calling on him

27:18.458 --> 27:20.625
as though he were
the missus next door.

27:20.709 --> 27:22.083
- Oh, come on, Carrie,

27:22.166 --> 27:24.583
can't a cat look at a king?

27:25.875 --> 27:27.291
- We should press
our advantage.

27:27.375 --> 27:30.500
- I think you overestimate
your advantage.

27:32.333 --> 27:35.291
[tense music]

27:35.375 --> 27:43.500
♪ ♪

27:46.917 --> 27:48.291
- This is the first time

27:48.375 --> 27:49.333
the issue of suffrage

27:49.417 --> 27:50.709
has been brought
to my attention.

27:50.792 --> 27:52.250
- Well, we hope that
you'll support the issue

27:52.333 --> 27:54.834
in your address to Congress,
Mr. President.

27:54.917 --> 27:57.458
- As I promised
in my election campaign,

27:57.542 --> 28:01.875
Congress will focus on currency
revision and tariff reform.

28:01.959 --> 28:04.041
These are issues which
affect all Americans

28:04.125 --> 28:08.250
and of course must take
priority over special interests.

28:10.250 --> 28:12.041
I can't very well
instruct Congress

28:12.125 --> 28:15.667
on the merits of an issue
I'm not familiar with.

28:15.750 --> 28:20.625
I hope you'll be patient
while I...educate myself.

28:25.250 --> 28:26.417
- Mr. President.

28:28.333 --> 28:30.250
How can you legislate
tariff reform

28:30.333 --> 28:32.875
when not all citizens
are able to vote for it?

28:32.959 --> 28:36.458
Isn't that why we fought
the American Revolution?

28:38.542 --> 28:41.792
["Gymnopedie No. 1"
by Eric Satie plays]

28:41.875 --> 28:49.875
♪ ♪

28:49.959 --> 28:54.709
The way he seated us
in a circle like schoolgirls.

28:54.792 --> 28:59.041
He's stalling, Lucy--he knows
Anna Shaw won't press him.

28:59.125 --> 29:00.959
- [crunching]

29:01.041 --> 29:03.834
What we need is
a separate committee

29:03.917 --> 29:05.542
dedicated
to the federal amendment

29:05.625 --> 29:07.208
and nothing else.
- Shh!

29:07.291 --> 29:15.333
♪  ♪

29:16.500 --> 29:18.583
- We've got women coming in
from every district

29:18.667 --> 29:19.917
to volunteer.

29:20.000 --> 29:23.125
Now's the time
to train them.

29:23.208 --> 29:26.041
Lobby Congress.

29:26.125 --> 29:27.375
Really pressure both houses,

29:27.458 --> 29:29.500
get the amendment on
the floor and to a vote.

29:29.583 --> 29:31.542
- It won't pass.
- Well, then we'll use that

29:31.625 --> 29:34.000
as an excuse to go after
the Democrats.

29:34.083 --> 29:35.625
We'll be a thorn
in Wilson's side.

29:35.709 --> 29:37.542
- Shh!
- A rock in his shoe.

29:37.625 --> 29:39.625
We won't...let up.

29:39.709 --> 29:42.834
["Gymnopedie No. 1"
continues]

29:42.917 --> 29:47.291
♪ ♪

29:47.375 --> 29:49.959
[whispering] Inez, we need
a bigger headquarters.

29:50.041 --> 29:52.333
Any of your rich boyfriends
own a building?

29:52.417 --> 29:54.291
- Would you please be quiet?

29:54.375 --> 29:57.208
- My sister's blind--I have to
read the titles to her.

29:57.291 --> 29:59.500
- That's it, you've ruined it
for me--let's go!

29:59.583 --> 30:02.250
Come on, let's go.
- Come on.

30:04.959 --> 30:06.834
- Oh.

30:06.917 --> 30:09.667
♪  ♪

30:09.750 --> 30:12.625
[upbeat music]

30:12.709 --> 30:15.291
Lucy: Instructions
for lobbyists.

30:15.375 --> 30:18.250
Before you visit a congressman,
look him up in our card index,

30:18.333 --> 30:20.041
what bills has he supported
in the past,

30:20.125 --> 30:21.333
what's his suffrage record.

30:21.417 --> 30:23.041
Learn the names
of his children.

30:23.125 --> 30:31.083
♪  ♪

30:33.083 --> 30:34.166
[doors closing]

30:34.250 --> 30:35.875
- We don't need women votin'

30:36.000 --> 30:37.250
in South Carolina.

30:37.333 --> 30:40.333
We know how to
take care of our women.

30:40.417 --> 30:42.875
- Be a good listener.
Don't interrupt.

30:42.959 --> 30:44.250
- Hi.

30:44.333 --> 30:46.500
- The majority of intelligent
refined, educated women

30:46.583 --> 30:48.625
in our country don't want it.

30:48.709 --> 30:49.875
And that's a fact.
[door closes]

30:49.959 --> 30:52.291
- Don't lose your temper.

30:56.500 --> 30:57.750
[door closes]

30:59.417 --> 31:01.792
man: ♪ I want you
to get together ♪

31:01.875 --> 31:04.166
- Well, since you are
suffragists,

31:04.250 --> 31:06.709
you won't mind standing.

31:08.750 --> 31:10.125
- I'm with you, I'm for it,

31:10.208 --> 31:12.875
I'm gonna vote for it.
Now don't bother me.

31:26.500 --> 31:27.875
- I was beginning to worry.

31:27.959 --> 31:31.041
- Didn't Mrs. Martin tell you
I was gonna be late?

31:31.125 --> 31:32.625
I asked her to call you.

31:32.709 --> 31:34.458
- Ohh, you look tired.

31:34.542 --> 31:37.875
- Suffrage amendment finally
made it out of committee.

31:37.959 --> 31:40.834
Took forever to defeat it.

31:40.917 --> 31:44.250
Senators love
to hear themselves talk.

31:46.083 --> 31:48.542
- What did they say?
Why did they vote it down?

31:48.625 --> 31:52.542
- Because, they know
that you have your hands full

31:52.625 --> 31:54.250
with the children already.

31:54.333 --> 31:55.500
- [scoffs]

31:56.834 --> 31:58.750
- Rebecca learn
any new words today?

31:58.834 --> 32:00.792
- Yes, "funny."

32:02.083 --> 32:03.917
- You didn't really expect
the amendment

32:04.000 --> 32:07.625
to get a 2/3rds majority,
did you?

32:07.709 --> 32:09.583
- I don't expect, I plan.

32:09.667 --> 32:13.083
For every possibility
I can imagine.

32:13.166 --> 32:15.000
- You don't like
surprises, hmm?

32:15.083 --> 32:16.500
- Not even
on my birthday.

32:16.583 --> 32:17.917
- [chuckles]

32:18.000 --> 32:21.500
Men plan, God laughs.

32:21.583 --> 32:23.667
- Yeah, well, I'm not a man.

32:23.750 --> 32:25.667
- Ever wish you were?

32:27.250 --> 32:28.917
- Once.

32:29.000 --> 32:31.667
I saw my brother peeing
his name in the snow.

32:31.750 --> 32:33.834
- [chuckles]

32:33.917 --> 32:36.875
Well, the wind
is changing.

32:42.041 --> 32:43.667
- Oh, what?

32:43.750 --> 32:47.125
- Alice Paul's new unauthorized
fundraising committee.

32:47.208 --> 32:49.458
She's calling it
"The Congressional Union".

32:49.542 --> 32:52.041
See who's on
the advisory board?

32:53.542 --> 32:55.458
- Not without my specs.

32:55.542 --> 32:56.917
- Phoebe Harkes,

32:57.000 --> 32:59.542
Helen Keller,
Harriot Blatch.

32:59.625 --> 33:02.083
She's handpicked
our best fundraisers.

33:03.542 --> 33:05.792
And that money should've
come here to the national

33:05.875 --> 33:09.125
for state campaigns,
not her propaganda sheet.

33:09.208 --> 33:11.834
You didn't authorize her
to publish a newspaper.

33:11.917 --> 33:13.208
- Of course not.

33:13.291 --> 33:14.875
- Well, read the editorial.

33:14.959 --> 33:18.625
She's telling women to boycott
Wilson in the next election.

33:18.709 --> 33:21.250
[energetic music]

33:21.333 --> 33:23.208
Lucy: Rarely in the history
of the country

33:23.291 --> 33:25.000
has a party
been more powerful

33:25.083 --> 33:28.583
than the Democratic party
is today.

33:28.667 --> 33:30.291
Those who hold power
are responsible

33:30.375 --> 33:34.792
not only for what they do
but for what they do not do.

33:34.875 --> 33:37.000
If the Democrats refuse
to enfranchise women,

33:37.083 --> 33:39.333
then it's incumbent
upon voters

33:39.417 --> 33:41.333
to boycott President Wilson
and his party

33:41.417 --> 33:43.667
in the upcoming election.

33:43.750 --> 33:45.333
President Wilson's inaction

33:45.417 --> 33:46.750
establishes just as
clear a record

33:46.834 --> 33:49.750
as does a policy
of open hostility.

33:51.750 --> 33:54.500
- Mm-mm, leave that--maybe
he'll feel he has to respond.

33:54.583 --> 33:57.250
- Wilson doesn't subscribe
to "The Suffragist."

33:57.333 --> 33:59.750
- He reads
"The Evening Star."

34:06.291 --> 34:07.917
[knocking on door]

34:12.208 --> 34:13.708
- Well, hello.

34:13.792 --> 34:16.333
- I apologize for not
returning your calls.

34:16.417 --> 34:18.125
- One call.

34:26.542 --> 34:27.667
- Yours?

34:29.542 --> 34:30.708
Hmm.

34:30.792 --> 34:32.333
It's the Colosseum,
isn't it?

34:32.417 --> 34:33.958
Have you been to Rome?

34:34.041 --> 34:36.166
- Are you trying
to make small talk?

34:36.250 --> 34:37.708
Because you stink at it.

34:37.792 --> 34:39.875
I know why you're here.

34:39.958 --> 34:42.083
The "Star" wouldn't
print some tirade

34:42.166 --> 34:43.667
from your propaganda sheet,
and you want me

34:43.750 --> 34:45.333
to grease the doors for you
here at the "Post."

34:45.417 --> 34:46.417
- "The Suffragist"
is not propaganda.

34:46.500 --> 34:47.792
It reports on suffrage news.

34:47.875 --> 34:49.708
And it's not a tirade.
It's an editorial.

34:49.792 --> 34:51.667
- This paper supports
the Democrats.

34:51.750 --> 34:54.041
Mr. Clayburgh isn't gonna
hand you editorial space.

34:54.125 --> 34:55.750
You want ink, buy a pen.

34:55.833 --> 34:58.083
- All I want is 15 minutes
with him.

34:58.166 --> 34:59.834
- Mm-hmm.

35:01.750 --> 35:03.792
- Could we talk about it
over lunch?

35:08.917 --> 35:11.625
- Dinner.
And don't wear that hat.

35:11.709 --> 35:13.083
- I like this hat.

35:13.166 --> 35:14.792
- It's ballast, isn't it?

35:14.875 --> 35:16.583
If you took it off,
you'd drift.

35:16.667 --> 35:18.125
You'd sleep late,

35:18.208 --> 35:20.709
you'd go to the park,
read magazines.

35:20.792 --> 35:23.000
- Detective novels.
- Go dancing.

35:23.083 --> 35:24.709
- Play tennis.

35:24.792 --> 35:26.083
- No rhythm?

35:26.166 --> 35:28.375
Am I getting too personal?

35:30.709 --> 35:32.750
I know what you're thinking.
- That saves time.

35:32.834 --> 35:34.250
- Dinner on Friday
work for you?

35:34.333 --> 35:35.667
- We must have
a bad connection.

35:35.750 --> 35:38.583
- Julia passed away
four years ago.

35:45.208 --> 35:46.667
Friday?

35:48.959 --> 35:50.333
- No night's good for me.

35:50.417 --> 35:52.083
- Is it because
I don't have a wife?

35:52.166 --> 35:53.500
- Because you're a coward

35:53.583 --> 35:56.417
who won't champion
a reasonable editorial.

35:58.250 --> 36:00.250
- Dinner, Francisco's,
Friday?

36:00.333 --> 36:01.542
- Bring your editor?

36:01.625 --> 36:04.417
- Ugh, all right,
whatever, come on.

36:17.834 --> 36:20.917
[women laughing]

36:31.709 --> 36:33.000
- Could you type this
for me?

36:33.083 --> 36:34.583
- Oh, I'm just here
to make a donation.

36:34.667 --> 36:36.000
- Well, it won't
take you long.

36:36.083 --> 36:37.250
The typewriter's here.

36:37.333 --> 36:39.458
- I don't know how
to type.

36:39.542 --> 36:41.125
- The letters
are on the keys.

36:41.208 --> 36:42.083
Thank you.

36:42.166 --> 36:45.959
[overlapping chatter]

37:05.291 --> 37:06.709
[knocking]

37:06.792 --> 37:07.917
Yes.

37:16.208 --> 37:17.667
Oh, thank you.

37:17.750 --> 37:19.166
Nice.

37:19.250 --> 37:20.458
Did you sign up for training?

37:20.542 --> 37:23.583
We need volunteers
to lobby for the amendment.

37:24.959 --> 37:29.125
- Um, I'm
Senator Leighton's wife.

37:29.208 --> 37:31.583
H-he doesn't approve.

37:31.667 --> 37:32.792
- If everyone approved

37:32.875 --> 37:35.542
there'd be no point to it,
would there?

37:37.291 --> 37:38.625
- Well,
I love my husband.

37:38.709 --> 37:42.667
I see no reason
to publicly embarrass him.

37:42.750 --> 37:43.959
- [deep sigh]

37:44.041 --> 37:46.709
Women like you are worse
than anti-suffragists.

37:46.792 --> 37:49.917
You perpetuate the lie
every day at breakfast.

37:50.000 --> 37:52.125
- I beg your pardon.

37:53.792 --> 37:56.333
You don't know what
you're talking about.

38:01.041 --> 38:02.291
[door closes]

38:04.917 --> 38:08.083
["Ain't She Sweet"
by Jimmy Lunceford]

38:08.166 --> 38:16.333
♪  ♪

38:24.959 --> 38:26.959
- Hi.
Mr. Weissman.

38:27.041 --> 38:29.834
- Of course.
Follow me.

38:29.917 --> 38:37.625
♪  ♪

38:37.709 --> 38:40.583
- My father
went to the bathroom.

39:03.333 --> 39:05.542
My shoe.

39:05.625 --> 39:07.250
It's untied.

39:10.375 --> 39:13.250
chorus: ♪  Ain't she sweet ♪

39:13.333 --> 39:16.417
♪  See her coming
down the street now ♪

39:16.500 --> 39:20.083
♪ Ask you very confidentially ♪

39:20.166 --> 39:22.250
♪  Ain't she sweet ♪

39:23.583 --> 39:24.625
- You mind?

39:27.166 --> 39:30.583
- He's the youngest newspaper
editor I've ever met.

39:30.667 --> 39:32.583
- Hmm...

39:32.667 --> 39:36.000
You want to
split the manicotti?

39:36.083 --> 39:39.125
♪ ♪

39:39.208 --> 39:42.041
[thunder rumbling]

39:42.125 --> 39:45.291
[rain pattering]

39:48.083 --> 39:50.166
- You're back early.

39:50.250 --> 39:53.333
- He had to take
his son home.

39:53.417 --> 39:55.125
- His son?

39:57.333 --> 39:59.834
Hey, my sister had the baby.

39:59.917 --> 40:02.583
A girl. She had a girl.

40:04.041 --> 40:07.709
God, one more year,
I'm gonna be 30.

40:07.792 --> 40:09.041
I can just see it now--

40:09.125 --> 40:13.333
I'll end up back in Brooklyn
with a hairless cat.

40:13.417 --> 40:15.250
Called Lester.

40:16.458 --> 40:17.709
- Leave the baby-making
to women

40:17.792 --> 40:19.709
who aren't lucky enough
to have your brains

40:19.792 --> 40:22.583
or your ability.

40:22.667 --> 40:25.375
Don't complicate your life.

40:25.458 --> 40:27.709
- My mother had eight of us.

40:27.792 --> 40:29.583
Elizabeth Cady Stanton
had seven.

40:29.667 --> 40:31.083
When she and Susan Anthony
were together,

40:31.166 --> 40:32.917
they took turns
feeding the babies.

40:33.000 --> 40:35.792
- I'm not feeding
anyone's babies.

40:35.875 --> 40:38.750
Are you done?
Let's go over the budget.

40:38.834 --> 40:40.917
- In the morning.
I'm too tired.

40:41.000 --> 40:44.333
- Think how tired you'd be
if you had seven children.

40:47.792 --> 40:50.000
- I'm tired of being alone.

40:52.000 --> 40:55.291
If you say you're not,
you're a liar.

41:04.542 --> 41:06.875
Anna: Before you sit down,
Miss Paul...

41:09.375 --> 41:12.750
$25,343.88

41:12.834 --> 41:13.875
is a very impressive total.

41:13.959 --> 41:16.542
Why hasn't any of that money

41:16.625 --> 41:18.500
been forwarded to
the national treasury?

41:18.583 --> 41:22.041
- It was collected by
the Congressional Union.

41:22.125 --> 41:23.458
The Union was created to fund

41:23.542 --> 41:24.959
the congressional
committee's efforts

41:25.041 --> 41:27.625
to lobby Washington
for a federal amendment.

41:27.709 --> 41:29.959
We're not budgeted
by the National Treasury.

41:30.041 --> 41:31.792
- I move to suspend
the activities

41:31.875 --> 41:33.458
of the congressional
committee

41:33.542 --> 41:36.458
during which time
the board will investigate

41:36.542 --> 41:39.208
unauthorized expenditures.

41:41.500 --> 41:42.625
- Second the motion.

41:42.709 --> 41:45.542
[dramatic music]

41:45.625 --> 41:53.291
♪ ♪

41:53.375 --> 41:54.959
Lucy: Did you hear that?

41:55.041 --> 41:57.625
Investigation
of our finances.

41:57.709 --> 42:00.291
Good, great, let them keep
their congressional committee.

42:00.375 --> 42:03.875
W e can run our own campaign.
The hell with NAWSA!

42:03.959 --> 42:06.750
- I don't want to
fight other women.

42:09.250 --> 42:13.333
- Well, Carrie Catt is the
next president of NAWSA.

42:13.417 --> 42:15.417
I don't think
she is a woman.

42:15.500 --> 42:17.959
[laughs]

42:18.041 --> 42:20.250
Seriously, has anyone
seen her naked?

42:31.542 --> 42:33.917
She called you a thief.

42:36.917 --> 42:38.583
If you don't resign
from the committee,

42:38.667 --> 42:42.375
she's gonna make sure you're
voted out, and then what?

42:42.458 --> 42:43.625
Hmm?

42:43.709 --> 42:45.500
We gonna fold our hands
like good little girls,

42:45.583 --> 42:47.250
do what Mama says,
hope that Wilson

42:47.333 --> 42:50.458
will pat us
on the fanny when he goes by?

42:57.166 --> 42:59.959
Look at me.

43:00.041 --> 43:03.333
No one will blame you
if we split with NAWSA.

43:03.417 --> 43:07.000
They're not giving us
any other choice.

43:15.166 --> 43:18.041
[bluesy music]

43:18.125 --> 43:22.083
♪ ♪

43:22.166 --> 43:27.166
woman: ♪ An ocean of you ♪

43:27.250 --> 43:30.375
♪  ♪

43:30.458 --> 43:32.959
♪ Lost in a wave ♪

43:33.041 --> 43:35.500
♪ Upon a face ♪

43:35.583 --> 43:43.417
♪  ♪

43:43.500 --> 43:48.417
♪ Under a blanket
of blue ♪

43:48.500 --> 43:50.250
- Here's your tea.

43:50.333 --> 43:52.417
- Thank you.

43:54.417 --> 43:57.709
woman: ♪ Lay sailin' ♪

43:57.792 --> 43:59.625
- Stick some on top.

43:59.709 --> 44:02.583
- Yeah, put your
tongue on your top.

44:02.667 --> 44:06.250
♪  ♪

44:06.333 --> 44:08.875
- Okay, get ready
for bed, come on.

44:08.959 --> 44:10.792
♪  ♪

44:10.875 --> 44:12.500
Okay?

44:12.583 --> 44:17.875
- ♪ Angel ♪

44:17.959 --> 44:21.959
♪  ♪

44:22.041 --> 44:26.041
♪ Ooh ♪

44:32.333 --> 44:35.959
- The National Woman's Party
is composed entirely of women

44:36.041 --> 44:39.166
and does not align itself
officially or unofficially

44:39.250 --> 44:41.792
with any existing
political party.

44:41.875 --> 44:46.000
The NWP does not put forth
a candidate for election.

44:46.083 --> 44:48.500
We are a single-platform party,

44:48.583 --> 44:50.125
dedicated to the passage

44:50.208 --> 44:52.750
of the following
constitutional amendment:

44:52.834 --> 44:56.083
The right of citizens of
the United States to vote

44:56.166 --> 44:59.333
shall not be denied or abridged
by the United States

44:59.417 --> 45:02.667
or any state,
on account of sex.

45:02.750 --> 45:04.500
We pledge unceasing
opposition

45:04.583 --> 45:07.041
to any and all
political candidates

45:07.125 --> 45:10.000
who refuse to support
this amendment.

45:10.083 --> 45:12.542
- And in the matter
of foreign trade,

45:12.625 --> 45:14.959
the economy demands--

45:20.166 --> 45:24.250
[applause, cheering]

45:26.083 --> 45:30.125
[laughter, chatter]

45:32.291 --> 45:34.041
- Hey!
- Ah, ah, ah--

45:34.125 --> 45:35.875
- Don't push, no pushing!

45:35.959 --> 45:37.417
- Mrs. Catt!
One question.

45:37.500 --> 45:39.834
- NAWSA does not support
the National Woman's Party.

45:39.917 --> 45:41.792
- Miss Paul said she plans
to organize women--

45:41.875 --> 45:43.709
- Miss Paul is taking
a thoughtless

45:43.792 --> 45:45.125
and irresponsible stance

45:45.208 --> 45:48.250
that amounts to an endorsement
of the Republican candidate.

45:48.333 --> 45:50.041
man: You think Alice Paul's
western campaign

45:50.125 --> 45:51.667
will cost Wilson
his re-election?

45:51.750 --> 45:53.917
- President Wilson has kept us
out of the war in Europe,

45:54.000 --> 45:55.625
and NAWSA will continue
to endorse him

45:55.709 --> 45:58.166
as will women voters
in the west.

46:05.000 --> 46:06.417
[band plays]

46:06.500 --> 46:08.250
boy: Extra, extra,
read all about it!

46:08.333 --> 46:10.333
Kaiser presses on,
read all about it.

46:10.417 --> 46:13.667
Extra, extra,
read all about it!

46:14.625 --> 46:15.959
Thank you, ma'am.

46:16.041 --> 46:18.458
- Oh, give this to Mrs. Harold
for expense money.

46:18.542 --> 46:19.750
She's a widow now.

46:19.834 --> 46:21.500
- Yeah, got it.

46:21.583 --> 46:23.417
- It isn't fair.

46:23.500 --> 46:25.041
♪ ♪

46:25.125 --> 46:26.834
- Should've called heads.

46:26.917 --> 46:28.083
Mrs. McEwan!

46:28.166 --> 46:30.166
Hey, buck up.
I'm only going to one state.

46:30.250 --> 46:31.417
I'll be
the first one back.

46:31.500 --> 46:32.917
Come here.

46:33.000 --> 46:34.250
- Alice?
- Yeah.

46:34.333 --> 46:35.959
- Alice, Inez wants you.
- Where is she?

46:36.041 --> 46:37.750
- She's by
the side entrance.

46:37.834 --> 46:41.333
- Bye, dear.
Bye.

46:41.417 --> 46:42.875
Bye-bye!

46:45.709 --> 46:47.875
- I, uh...

46:47.959 --> 46:49.917
I can't go to California.

46:50.000 --> 46:52.166
You have to find
someone else.

46:52.250 --> 46:53.291
- There is no one else.

46:53.375 --> 46:54.417
You're the woman
on the horse.

46:54.500 --> 46:55.458
You can make
or break a rally.

46:55.542 --> 46:58.542
- Alice,
I can't tell you--

47:00.458 --> 47:02.834
I'm sorry,
I'm exhausted.

47:02.917 --> 47:04.500
- Run around Europe,

47:04.583 --> 47:06.583
waste your time
on peace missions,

47:06.667 --> 47:08.291
and now you bail
when it really matters?

47:08.375 --> 47:09.750
- Waste my time?

47:09.834 --> 47:11.500
You couldn't say that
if you'd been with me in France.

47:11.583 --> 47:13.417
- We're not in France,
we're in the United States,

47:13.500 --> 47:15.458
and people want to hear
Inez Milholland.

47:15.542 --> 47:18.917
- Oh, stuff 'em, nothing's more
important than ending a war.

47:19.000 --> 47:20.417
Not suffrage, not anything.

47:20.500 --> 47:23.208
You can't understand
until you've seen it.

47:23.291 --> 47:26.333
- Inez, this is
an election year.

47:26.417 --> 47:29.166
- And you're wearing
blinders.

47:29.250 --> 47:31.792
- I'm seeing
around the corner.

47:31.875 --> 47:34.500
You hear that?
It's a military band.

47:34.583 --> 47:36.333
You want a war,
here's your war.

47:36.417 --> 47:39.000
This war's been going on
for over half a century.

47:39.083 --> 47:41.500
The women who started it
are dead and buried.

47:41.583 --> 47:44.041
Here is where it ends.
Now is when we win!

47:44.125 --> 47:46.709
You're tired, I'm tired,
who isn't tired?

47:46.792 --> 47:48.500
But don't sit down yet.

47:48.583 --> 47:50.000
If the woman on the horse
drops out,

47:50.083 --> 47:52.917
what message is that
gonna send the troops?

47:55.750 --> 47:59.375
- Oh, God.

47:59.458 --> 48:01.709
I can't say no to you.

48:01.792 --> 48:04.125
- Then why try?

48:09.291 --> 48:12.959
Get some sleep on the train.
You look awful.

48:13.041 --> 48:14.792
That's the spirit!

48:17.959 --> 48:21.625
[church bell tolls]

48:34.625 --> 48:35.834
[tapping]

48:46.500 --> 48:48.917
- Even God
rested on Sunday.

48:49.000 --> 48:52.500
Come on.
I'll let you drive.

48:54.291 --> 48:56.250
- I'm busy.

48:56.333 --> 48:58.208
- Well, you do know
how to drive,

48:58.291 --> 49:00.542
don't you, Miss Paul?

49:00.625 --> 49:02.709
- Is that a car
or a quilt?

49:02.792 --> 49:04.500
- [chuckles]

49:04.583 --> 49:06.208
You want to learn?

49:08.041 --> 49:09.250
Easy!
[stammering]

49:09.333 --> 49:10.750
You gotta
keep your head up

49:10.834 --> 49:12.083
when you're driving.

49:12.166 --> 49:14.667
It's very important
to watch the road.

49:14.750 --> 49:16.625
Little easier when you
let out on the clutch.

49:16.709 --> 49:17.875
Okay, there we are.

49:17.959 --> 49:20.583
That's better.
Now, watch the road.

49:20.667 --> 49:21.875
Watch the road.
Keep your head up.

49:22.000 --> 49:23.667
Don't look so tense.
Watch the road.

49:23.750 --> 49:25.333
Watch the road--
watch the tree!

49:25.417 --> 49:27.417
- Whoa!

49:29.041 --> 49:31.083
- Not the clutch,
the brake, the brake.

49:31.166 --> 49:36.542
♪  ♪

49:36.625 --> 49:38.458
[ducks quacking]

49:38.542 --> 49:42.208
My little sister picked it up
just like that.

49:44.959 --> 49:47.375
You look at your feet
when you dance, don't you?

49:47.458 --> 49:50.041
- I'm a Quaker.
We don't dance.

49:54.709 --> 49:57.166
What?
- Take off the damn hat.

50:12.959 --> 50:15.875
Hmm.

50:15.959 --> 50:17.208
Okay.

50:17.291 --> 50:20.083
Come on now,
put it in reverse.

50:20.166 --> 50:21.917
Keep your head up.
Don't look down.

50:22.000 --> 50:25.333
[Sarah McLachlan's "Fumbling
Toward Ecstasy" plays]

50:25.417 --> 50:31.583
♪ ♪

50:31.667 --> 50:34.959
McLachlan: ♪ All the fear
has left me now ♪

50:35.041 --> 50:37.542
♪  ♪

50:37.625 --> 50:41.041
♪ I'm not frightened
anymore ♪

50:42.458 --> 50:46.333
♪ It's my heart that pounds
beneath my flesh ♪

50:46.417 --> 50:48.291
♪  ♪

50:48.375 --> 50:52.041
♪ It's my mouth that
pushes out this breath ♪

50:52.125 --> 51:00.166
♪  ♪

51:05.750 --> 51:11.417
♪ And if I shed a tear
I won't cage it ♪

51:11.500 --> 51:14.208
♪ I won't fear love ♪

51:14.291 --> 51:16.625
♪ ♪

51:16.709 --> 51:22.709
♪ And if I feel a rage
I won't deny it ♪

51:22.792 --> 51:25.750
♪ I won't fear love ♪

51:25.834 --> 51:34.000
♪  ♪

51:49.959 --> 51:55.458
♪ Peace on the way ♪

51:55.542 --> 51:58.709
♪ To comfort ♪

51:58.792 --> 52:05.417
♪ Oh, and if I shed a tear
I won't cage it ♪

52:05.500 --> 52:08.041
♪ I won't fear love ♪

52:08.125 --> 52:10.667
♪  ♪

52:10.750 --> 52:15.542
♪ Oh, and if I feel a rage
I won't deny it ♪

52:15.625 --> 52:17.542
- All right, Miss Jenny.

52:21.250 --> 52:22.291
[laughter]

52:22.375 --> 52:23.583
- Look at you.

52:23.667 --> 52:26.333
[laughter, chatter]

52:27.583 --> 52:29.500
- All right, love.

52:29.583 --> 52:32.083
- Did you see
the paper?

52:33.083 --> 52:35.792
[nanny and girl
murmuring]

52:35.875 --> 52:40.959
"The National Woman's Party
is traveling west by train.

52:41.041 --> 52:43.000
"They will embark on
a speaking campaign

52:43.083 --> 52:44.959
"urging women voters to vote

52:45.041 --> 52:47.709
"against the Democrats
in this election

52:47.792 --> 52:49.583
"who oppose
a federal amendment.

52:49.667 --> 52:52.333
"Noted contributors
to this effort

52:52.417 --> 52:57.083
include
Mrs. Thomas Leighton."

52:58.709 --> 53:01.834
- I used my housekeeping
allowance, that's all.

53:01.917 --> 53:03.458
It has nothing
to do with you.

53:03.542 --> 53:05.917
- Emily,
I'm a Democratic senator.

53:06.000 --> 53:08.375
You're my wife.

53:08.458 --> 53:11.500
It's got everything
to do with me!

53:11.583 --> 53:14.166
You'll withdraw
your membership.

53:14.250 --> 53:17.041
- They count on my
monthly contributions.

53:19.000 --> 53:20.875
- I've closed your account.

53:20.959 --> 53:24.959
You can charge
at the grocers,

53:25.041 --> 53:28.417
and the bills will be
sent to my office.

53:40.250 --> 53:42.125
- Mr. President,

53:42.208 --> 53:44.709
how long must women wait
for liberty?

53:44.792 --> 53:47.625
- Wilson: I do not believe
that women will vote

53:47.709 --> 53:50.375
in a national election.

53:50.458 --> 53:52.709
- Inez: We declare our faith

53:52.792 --> 53:54.792
in the principles
of self-government.

53:54.875 --> 53:56.542
- Wilson: If they were to,
they would not be

53:56.625 --> 53:59.208
as intelligent
as I think they are.

53:59.291 --> 54:02.250
Inez: That woman,
irrespective of her race,

54:02.333 --> 54:05.709
was made first
for her own happiness

54:05.792 --> 54:07.709
with the absolute right
to herself

54:07.792 --> 54:09.458
to all opportunities
life affords.

54:09.542 --> 54:12.500
- Women should be patient,
and continue to work

54:12.583 --> 54:15.583
in the admirable way
they have worked in the past,

54:15.667 --> 54:19.375
campaigning for suffrage
state by state.

54:19.458 --> 54:27.625
♪  ♪

54:39.166 --> 54:44.208
- We ask of our rulers
no special favors,

54:44.291 --> 54:48.000
no special privileges...

54:48.083 --> 54:49.625
no special legislation.

54:49.709 --> 54:51.917
Wilson: I am very glad
to make my position

54:52.000 --> 54:54.417
about the suffrage
quite clear to you.

54:54.500 --> 54:56.041
My private thoughts aside,

54:56.125 --> 54:58.959
I'm not at liberty
to urge upon Congress

54:59.041 --> 55:00.667
policies which
are not supported

55:00.750 --> 55:03.125
by the party for whom
I am a spokesperson.

55:03.208 --> 55:05.959
- We ask justice.

55:06.041 --> 55:08.458
We ask equality.

55:08.542 --> 55:12.709
We ask that all
of the, uh...

55:14.291 --> 55:16.792
The civil and political rights

55:16.875 --> 55:20.375
that belong to citizens
of the United States

55:20.458 --> 55:24.834
be, uh, be guaranteed

55:24.917 --> 55:26.875
to us

55:26.959 --> 55:31.291
and our daughters...

55:31.375 --> 55:32.917
forever.

55:33.000 --> 55:36.000
[dramatic music]

55:36.083 --> 55:44.250
♪ ♪

55:55.709 --> 55:58.583
[somber music]

55:58.667 --> 56:06.583
♪ ♪

56:23.709 --> 56:25.250
- What?

56:27.959 --> 56:29.458
What, Lucy?

56:31.250 --> 56:33.291
- Inez...

56:33.375 --> 56:36.208
collapsed...

56:36.291 --> 56:38.959
and they took her
to the hospital.

56:41.250 --> 56:45.250
- But she's all right,
isn't she?

56:57.041 --> 56:59.709
[somber music]

56:59.792 --> 57:08.000
♪ ♪

57:22.041 --> 57:23.500
women, whispering:
Dear Inez...

57:23.583 --> 57:26.166
[woman speaks native language]

57:28.875 --> 57:31.166
- My dear Inez...
[echoing] Inez...

57:31.250 --> 57:33.000
- Dearest Inez...

57:33.083 --> 57:36.917
[somber music]

57:37.000 --> 57:40.000
- Dear Inez...
[echoing] Dear Inez...

57:41.166 --> 57:42.750
- Thank you.

57:46.333 --> 57:50.208
- Dear Inez...
[echoing] Dear Inez...Inez...

58:01.375 --> 58:04.458
Emily:
How can death claim you?

58:04.542 --> 58:09.542
And I, remembering how
the faces of many women

58:09.625 --> 58:12.667
turned toward you
with expectation...

58:12.750 --> 58:15.417
♪  ♪

58:15.500 --> 58:18.709
[melody picks up]

58:18.792 --> 58:26.000
♪ ♪

58:26.083 --> 58:28.250
How can I find consolation?

58:28.333 --> 58:36.458
♪  ♪

59:02.208 --> 59:05.625
- Lucy Burns called, again.

59:11.417 --> 59:15.041
You are being ridiculous.

59:15.125 --> 59:17.542
She was a grown woman.

59:17.625 --> 59:20.667
She knew she had
pernicious anemia.

59:23.750 --> 59:25.333
Stop blaming yourself.

59:25.417 --> 59:28.458
- My coming home has nothing
to do with Inez.

59:28.542 --> 59:30.583
Campaign's over, that's all.

59:33.000 --> 59:34.709
- You put your hand
to the plow,

59:34.792 --> 59:36.500
you finish the row.

59:40.667 --> 59:43.542
[dramatic music]

59:43.625 --> 59:51.834
♪  ♪

01:00:15.083 --> 01:00:17.166
- What are you
doing up here?

01:00:17.250 --> 01:00:18.917
- Canning fruit.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:21.083
- What fruit?
It's winter.

01:00:21.166 --> 01:00:23.500
- Winter fruit.

01:00:25.500 --> 01:00:27.417
- You needed a rest, okay,
you had a rest.

01:00:27.500 --> 01:00:29.917
You feel bad about Inez.
We all do.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:33.166
It's awful,
but it's not over.

01:00:40.709 --> 01:00:43.875
- Inez was tired.
She asked me to replace her.

01:00:43.959 --> 01:00:46.208
- [sighs]

01:00:48.375 --> 01:00:49.792
Nobody ever made
Inez Milholland

01:00:49.875 --> 01:00:51.375
do anything in her life.

01:00:51.458 --> 01:00:53.000
- She couldn't say no to me.

01:00:53.083 --> 01:00:55.458
Don't you read the
"Ladies Home Journal"?

01:00:55.542 --> 01:00:56.667
"Alice Paul's relentless.

01:00:56.750 --> 01:00:58.875
Do it for suffrage,
do it for suffrage."

01:00:58.959 --> 01:01:00.542
- That's what
we need to hear.

01:01:00.625 --> 01:01:03.083
- Well, get a parrot.
- Don't use her as an excuse.

01:01:03.166 --> 01:01:05.166
She would hate that.

01:01:08.667 --> 01:01:11.750
[owl hoots]

01:01:14.542 --> 01:01:19.125
- She said,
"Men plan, God laughs."

01:01:25.166 --> 01:01:28.166
[chokes back tears]

01:01:28.250 --> 01:01:35.875
♪  ♪

01:01:35.959 --> 01:01:39.750
You ever wonder what
we're doing, Lucy?

01:01:43.166 --> 01:01:46.291
'Cause it seems like
He is laughing.

01:01:48.208 --> 01:01:51.417
And it's so unfair.

01:01:52.458 --> 01:01:54.667
That anyone should
have to die in a fight

01:01:54.750 --> 01:01:57.458
that shouldn't even
be a fight.

01:01:59.667 --> 01:02:01.959
Especially her.

01:02:05.542 --> 01:02:07.041
Isn't it ridiculous?

01:02:07.125 --> 01:02:09.458
[sobs, sniffles]

01:02:13.291 --> 01:02:15.166
She's dead.

01:02:15.250 --> 01:02:17.333
And we're right
where we started,

01:02:17.417 --> 01:02:19.250
which is nowhere at all.

01:02:23.834 --> 01:02:24.875
[sighs]

01:02:24.959 --> 01:02:27.375
I'm lost, Lucy.

01:02:27.458 --> 01:02:33.875
♪  ♪

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:37.917
- We laugh, too.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:41.125
Remember?
In London?

01:02:42.583 --> 01:02:44.542
That time that we hid
in the coat closet

01:02:44.625 --> 01:02:46.875
so we could
interrupt Parliament...

01:02:46.959 --> 01:02:49.208
[chuckles]

01:02:49.291 --> 01:02:52.375
And you had to pee.

01:02:52.458 --> 01:02:54.750
And I said to you,
I said, "Hey,

01:02:54.834 --> 01:02:57.375
"hey, here's some
lord's boot.

01:02:57.458 --> 01:03:00.417
Go ahead, go ahead."

01:03:00.500 --> 01:03:02.917
I thought to myself,
"If she's game for that,

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:06.667
that's it, we're gonna be
friends for life."

01:03:10.166 --> 01:03:12.083
We laughed,

01:03:12.166 --> 01:03:15.750
and we can still laugh.

01:03:15.834 --> 01:03:18.792
I don't see that there is
any other way, you know.

01:03:18.875 --> 01:03:20.792
That is what we do,
we piss in the boot.

01:03:20.875 --> 01:03:24.709
We come out,
guns blazing, yeah.

01:03:30.917 --> 01:03:34.792
I wish Alice
was here, yeah.

01:03:34.875 --> 01:03:38.542
My friend Alice.
You can't say no to her.

01:03:38.625 --> 01:03:40.917
It's beautiful.

01:03:43.917 --> 01:03:46.375
Hey.

01:03:49.792 --> 01:03:52.792
Heads, we'll milk cows.

01:03:52.875 --> 01:03:56.709
Tails, we'll go find
Wilson's boots, hmm?

01:04:04.750 --> 01:04:08.041
[anticipatory music]

01:04:08.125 --> 01:04:16.250
♪ ♪

01:04:25.959 --> 01:04:29.291
- [speaking under breath]

01:04:38.667 --> 01:04:39.583
[sighs]

01:04:39.667 --> 01:04:47.792
♪  ♪

01:04:52.917 --> 01:04:57.333
- Has there been any reaction
from the president?

01:04:57.417 --> 01:04:58.959
Who knew about this?

01:05:35.667 --> 01:05:38.500
- The National Woman's Party
will station sentinels

01:05:38.583 --> 01:05:40.083
at the White House gate

01:05:40.166 --> 01:05:41.917
from dawn until dusk,
every day,

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:44.750
until the Constitution
of the United States is amended

01:05:44.834 --> 01:05:48.000
to ensure that every citizen,
regardless of sex,

01:05:48.083 --> 01:05:50.542
is entitled to vote
for the man who--

01:05:50.625 --> 01:05:52.417
- Or woman.

01:05:52.500 --> 01:05:54.500
- Or woman...
[all chuckle]

01:05:54.583 --> 01:05:56.083
Who occupies that house.

01:05:56.166 --> 01:05:58.792
Give that good boy
an extra cookie.

01:05:58.875 --> 01:06:00.333
- "Silent,
silly and offensive.

01:06:00.417 --> 01:06:02.417
"A man's mind would
never dream of something

01:06:02.500 --> 01:06:04.333
at once so petty
and so monstrous."

01:06:04.417 --> 01:06:05.625
Oh, listen to this.

01:06:05.709 --> 01:06:07.333
"The demonstration was
denounced by president

01:06:07.417 --> 01:06:09.625
"of the National American
Woman Suffrage Association,

01:06:09.709 --> 01:06:11.041
"Mrs. Carrie Chapman Catt

01:06:11.125 --> 01:06:13.375
who pointed out that the NWP,"
which is us,

01:06:13.458 --> 01:06:17.458
"represents only 10%
of the nation's suffragists."

01:06:17.542 --> 01:06:19.125
Is that true,
did she make that up?

01:06:19.208 --> 01:06:20.709
I think she might have
made that up.

01:06:20.792 --> 01:06:22.166
- What's that?
What are you doing?

01:06:22.250 --> 01:06:24.333
- I'm heating up bricks
for the girls to stand on.

01:06:24.417 --> 01:06:25.458
It's freezing out there.

01:06:25.542 --> 01:06:27.500
- Give them double coats.

01:06:27.583 --> 01:06:28.458
Check to see who can donate

01:06:28.542 --> 01:06:29.875
coats, gloves,
sweaters, scarves.

01:06:29.959 --> 01:06:31.166
Try Mrs. Belmont.

01:06:31.250 --> 01:06:32.792
- "The president smiled
and waved to the ladies

01:06:32.875 --> 01:06:35.333
as his automobile
swept into the grounds."

01:06:35.417 --> 01:06:37.458
- Oh, phony baloney
[says foreign word].

01:06:37.542 --> 01:06:39.959
- "Mr. and Mrs. Richard Lane
announce the marriage

01:06:40.041 --> 01:06:43.500
of their daughter Susan
to Roland Ashmore."

01:06:43.583 --> 01:06:45.583
Just trying to mix it up.

01:06:48.542 --> 01:06:49.959
"Captain of British steamer

01:06:50.041 --> 01:06:53.000
"made prisoner by German U-boat.

01:06:53.083 --> 01:06:56.208
German submarines
sink five more ships."

01:07:04.667 --> 01:07:12.750
♪  ♪

01:07:16.583 --> 01:07:19.250
- They're within
their legal rights.

01:07:21.500 --> 01:07:23.333
- They'll get tired
of the cold.

01:07:23.417 --> 01:07:24.500
It won't last.

01:07:24.583 --> 01:07:26.166
- Good to see you,
Mr. President.

01:07:26.250 --> 01:07:28.959
[thunder rumbles]

01:07:30.709 --> 01:07:35.291
- ♪ I'm like the rain,
I'm coming in ♪

01:07:35.375 --> 01:07:39.417
♪ Although
you're hiding from me ♪

01:07:39.500 --> 01:07:44.417
♪ I'm like that voice
inside your head ♪

01:07:44.500 --> 01:07:46.375
♪  ♪

01:07:46.458 --> 01:07:48.500
♪ Can you hear me? ♪

01:07:48.583 --> 01:07:51.333
♪ Can you hear me,
can you hear me ♪

01:07:51.417 --> 01:07:53.750
- How about
they're trespassing?

01:07:53.834 --> 01:07:56.542
- On public property?

01:07:56.625 --> 01:07:57.917
- Oh, yeah.

01:08:00.500 --> 01:08:03.750
Emily: The avenue
is misty gray,

01:08:03.834 --> 01:08:07.208
and here beside
the guarded gate

01:08:07.291 --> 01:08:11.709
we hold our golden,
blowing flags

01:08:11.792 --> 01:08:14.750
and wait.

01:08:14.834 --> 01:08:16.125
man: Emily?

01:08:17.667 --> 01:08:19.125
Emily?

01:08:19.207 --> 01:08:22.917
♪  ♪

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:28.166
woman: ♪ I'm like that voice
inside your head ♪

01:08:28.250 --> 01:08:32.082
♪  ♪

01:08:32.166 --> 01:08:34.417
♪ Can you hear me ♪

01:08:34.500 --> 01:08:36.582
♪ Can you hear me ♪

01:08:36.667 --> 01:08:39.125
♪ Can you hear me ♪

01:08:39.207 --> 01:08:42.417
♪  ♪

01:08:42.500 --> 01:08:44.207
- Senator Myers
drafted a bill

01:08:44.291 --> 01:08:46.125
that would outlaw
treasonous banners.

01:08:46.207 --> 01:08:49.709
- Those banners
quote the president.

01:08:49.792 --> 01:08:52.625
woman: ♪ Can you hear me ♪

01:08:52.709 --> 01:08:55.332
- You're a brave girl.

01:08:55.417 --> 01:08:58.457
♪ ♪

01:08:58.542 --> 01:09:02.625
woman: ♪ Can you hear me ♪

01:09:02.709 --> 01:09:04.917
♪ Can you hear me ♪

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:09.917
- This continued picketing
by the National Woman's Party

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:12.542
is the single
greatest obstacle

01:09:12.625 --> 01:09:14.875
to the suffrage amendment.

01:09:16.207 --> 01:09:18.250
We do not support it

01:09:18.332 --> 01:09:21.166
and we have made that clear
to the president.

01:09:22.750 --> 01:09:24.332
Doris: The suffrage committee
from Michigan

01:09:24.417 --> 01:09:25.667
is here to pick up their bus.

01:09:25.750 --> 01:09:27.332
Can we put them--
- Ask Mrs. Lewis.

01:09:27.417 --> 01:09:28.917
- Toilet's not working
in the upstairs bathroom.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:30.041
- Ask Mabel.

01:09:30.125 --> 01:09:32.207
- Can I have dinner
with Ben Weissman?

01:09:32.291 --> 01:09:33.332
- Ask your mother.

01:09:33.417 --> 01:09:34.582
- I don't want to
step on your toes.

01:09:34.667 --> 01:09:36.166
So you're not seeing him?
- No.

01:09:36.250 --> 01:09:38.082
- Well, that's what
I told Lucy, but--

01:09:44.125 --> 01:09:46.792
[teeth being brushed]

01:09:48.207 --> 01:09:50.582
- Heard you gave away your beau.

01:09:52.625 --> 01:09:53.625
- Beau?

01:09:53.709 --> 01:09:54.750
- [spits]

01:09:54.834 --> 01:09:56.083
Pardon my French.

01:09:56.166 --> 01:09:59.750
- If you mean Weissman,
he's not and I didn't.

01:10:01.667 --> 01:10:07.208
- He only asked Doris out
because you never say yes.

01:10:07.291 --> 01:10:09.667
Don't you want
to get married, Alice?

01:10:09.750 --> 01:10:11.375
- I'm busy that day.

01:10:11.458 --> 01:10:14.709
- All the men I meet
are idiots.

01:10:14.792 --> 01:10:18.291
Or terrified of me.

01:10:18.375 --> 01:10:21.250
But if I met someone
like Weissman,

01:10:21.333 --> 01:10:24.875
I would latch onto him
like a mollusk.

01:10:24.959 --> 01:10:27.875
- It wouldn't be fair.

01:10:27.959 --> 01:10:31.792
To him or Michael.
A little boy needs a mother.

01:10:33.709 --> 01:10:36.041
My whole heart's
in this fight.

01:10:36.125 --> 01:10:39.125
There's nothing to spare,
not if I mean to win.

01:10:39.208 --> 01:10:42.250
- You underestimate
your heart.

01:10:46.834 --> 01:10:49.125
- When you're alone...

01:10:53.875 --> 01:10:57.417
You can make any
choice you want.

01:10:57.500 --> 01:11:01.166
But when someone loves you,
you lose that right.

01:11:03.542 --> 01:11:07.959
I won't give anything away
until we have it all.

01:11:09.375 --> 01:11:11.333
I can't.

01:11:19.709 --> 01:11:23.375
- Everything's a trade-off,
isn't it?

01:11:26.041 --> 01:11:28.834
- Seems to be.

01:11:35.917 --> 01:11:38.667
- Tom, I need--I need--

01:11:38.750 --> 01:11:40.959
I need to tell--
I need to tell you--

01:11:41.041 --> 01:11:44.875
I need to...
I want to tell you.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.291
Tom, I...

01:11:53.375 --> 01:11:56.375
I n--I need--

01:11:56.458 --> 01:11:58.125
Yeah.

01:11:58.208 --> 01:11:59.792
Tom...

01:11:59.875 --> 01:12:01.333
[door opens]

01:12:02.625 --> 01:12:04.375
[door closes]

01:12:05.542 --> 01:12:07.583
Tom, I have something to--

01:12:12.750 --> 01:12:14.125
To...

01:12:14.208 --> 01:12:17.375
- Looks like we've had
enough of Kaiser Wilhelm.

01:12:19.625 --> 01:12:21.792
United States
is declaring war.

01:12:21.875 --> 01:12:24.709
[dramatic music]

01:12:24.792 --> 01:12:32.917
♪ ♪

01:12:35.417 --> 01:12:37.333
- There are, it may be,

01:12:37.417 --> 01:12:40.500
many months
of fiery sacrifice

01:12:40.583 --> 01:12:42.750
and trials ahead of us.

01:12:42.834 --> 01:12:45.500
It is a fearful thing to lead
this great peaceful people

01:12:45.583 --> 01:12:47.166
into war...

01:12:47.250 --> 01:12:50.667
- "Into the most terrible
and disastrous of all wars.

01:12:50.750 --> 01:12:52.166
"We shall fight
for the things

01:12:52.250 --> 01:12:56.000
which we have always carried
nearest our hearts."

01:12:56.083 --> 01:12:58.417
- "We shall fight
for democracy,

01:12:58.500 --> 01:13:00.917
"for the right of those
who submit to authority

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:03.709
to have a voice in
their own governments."

01:13:03.792 --> 01:13:06.041
[snorts] Wilson's going to
fight for their rights?

01:13:06.125 --> 01:13:07.542
- No, no, he's not gonna fight.

01:13:07.625 --> 01:13:09.625
He's gonna send men to fight
the Kaiser for him.

01:13:09.709 --> 01:13:11.583
He's gonna stay right here
and tip his hat

01:13:11.667 --> 01:13:13.917
to all the American women
standing at his gate.

01:13:14.000 --> 01:13:16.291
- There won't be any women
standing at his gate.

01:13:16.375 --> 01:13:18.041
- What?
- We can't picket

01:13:18.125 --> 01:13:20.709
a wartime president.
Ruza: Why the hell not?

01:13:20.792 --> 01:13:22.250
- It's treason,
that's why.

01:13:22.333 --> 01:13:23.834
Lucy: Treason is betraying
your country.

01:13:23.917 --> 01:13:27.125
Partitioning is not treason.
At worst, it's just rude.

01:13:27.208 --> 01:13:31.667
- Give it any name you want.
The war changes everything.

01:13:31.750 --> 01:13:32.959
- This is not our war.

01:13:33.041 --> 01:13:35.166
- Women have husbands.
Women have sons.

01:13:35.250 --> 01:13:36.417
- No one's gonna thank us

01:13:36.500 --> 01:13:38.333
if we all slink off
to roll bandages.

01:13:38.417 --> 01:13:39.959
- Not about being
thanked.

01:13:40.041 --> 01:13:43.000
- This is my country, and if
our soldiers need bandages,

01:13:43.083 --> 01:13:44.166
I'm rolling bandages.

01:13:44.250 --> 01:13:45.625
- Roll them
on the picket line.

01:13:45.709 --> 01:13:47.750
- Look, we kicked ourselves
when we dropped the cause

01:13:47.834 --> 01:13:49.583
during the Civil War,
and what happened?

01:13:49.667 --> 01:13:51.417
Congress gave
Negro men the vote

01:13:51.500 --> 01:13:52.750
- Yes.
- And told women to wait

01:13:52.834 --> 01:13:53.667
their turn, right?

01:13:53.750 --> 01:13:56.166
- And we're still
waiting.

01:13:56.250 --> 01:13:58.917
- Tell me to be there
and I will.

01:13:59.000 --> 01:14:00.959
- Be there, right?

01:14:04.083 --> 01:14:05.834
Right?
Alice, tell her.

01:14:08.875 --> 01:14:10.667
- Inez said there was
nothing more important

01:14:10.750 --> 01:14:12.959
than ending a war.

01:14:13.041 --> 01:14:15.000
- Jesus, Mary and Joseph.

01:14:19.667 --> 01:14:21.709
[horn toots]

01:14:25.250 --> 01:14:28.041
Hey. You wanna go put
your ear to your desk?

01:14:28.125 --> 01:14:32.000
- If we push Wilson now,
there's gonna be consequences.

01:14:32.083 --> 01:14:33.291
- Yeah.

01:14:33.375 --> 01:14:34.792
- For everyone.

01:14:34.875 --> 01:14:37.792
- Land hard, roll left.

01:14:37.875 --> 01:14:39.917
"We shall fight
for democracy."

01:14:40.000 --> 01:14:41.500
He said it!

01:14:41.583 --> 01:14:45.041
He should have to
eat it and choke.

01:14:46.667 --> 01:14:48.625
I'm not saying that
we ignore the war.

01:14:48.709 --> 01:14:51.875
I'm saying that we
saddle up and fight it.

01:14:51.959 --> 01:14:53.583
He can't fight
for democracy abroad

01:14:53.667 --> 01:14:56.375
and deny it here at home,
he can't.

01:14:58.542 --> 01:15:00.208
- No mothers
on the picket line.

01:15:00.291 --> 01:15:02.041
- And no Alice Paul
on the picket line either.

01:15:02.125 --> 01:15:03.625
- I can't ask women to
risk it

01:15:03.709 --> 01:15:05.333
unless I risk it with them.
- Alice, listen to me.

01:15:05.417 --> 01:15:07.208
- No one's on the line
if I'm not on the line.

01:15:07.291 --> 01:15:08.834
- I'll be us on the picket line.
Don't argue with me.

01:15:08.917 --> 01:15:10.208
You're Mama Duck,
we follow you.

01:15:10.291 --> 01:15:12.000
If you go down,
they'll scatter.

01:15:12.083 --> 01:15:13.125
Use your head.

01:15:13.208 --> 01:15:15.375
One of us on the line
is enough.

01:15:15.458 --> 01:15:16.667
- I'll flip you for it.

01:15:16.750 --> 01:15:18.208
- No, it has to be me.

01:15:18.291 --> 01:15:20.208
I photograph
better than you.

01:15:20.291 --> 01:15:28.291
♪  ♪

01:15:32.291 --> 01:15:35.709
- I can't tell you...

01:15:35.792 --> 01:15:38.417
what's right and
what's wrong, not now.

01:15:38.500 --> 01:15:40.375
Not this time.

01:15:42.083 --> 01:15:46.834
I thought about what
I would say to you.

01:15:46.917 --> 01:15:49.125
You've all worked
so hard for so long,

01:15:49.208 --> 01:15:53.375
and I am grateful
to all of you.

01:15:53.458 --> 01:15:55.792
No matter what you decide,

01:15:55.875 --> 01:15:58.291
no one will judge you.

01:15:58.375 --> 01:16:00.375
Certainly not me.

01:16:00.458 --> 01:16:08.583
♪  ♪

01:16:09.709 --> 01:16:10.667
- [scoffs]

01:16:10.750 --> 01:16:14.041
[energetic music]

01:16:14.125 --> 01:16:22.291
♪ ♪

01:16:34.583 --> 01:16:36.667
man: Oh, my gosh.
- What is this?

01:16:36.750 --> 01:16:38.083
man: You ladies,
what are you thinking?

01:16:38.166 --> 01:16:39.250
man: How dare you!

01:16:39.333 --> 01:16:42.208
Our country's at war!

01:16:42.291 --> 01:16:44.417
Shame on you!
Shame on you all!

01:16:44.500 --> 01:16:48.166
- Never thought they'd picket
a wartime president.

01:16:48.250 --> 01:16:50.750
- Public opinion
may put a stop to it.

01:16:50.834 --> 01:16:52.417
- And if it doesn't?

01:16:52.500 --> 01:16:54.208
- The president
needs your support!

01:16:54.291 --> 01:16:56.667
Maybe you should
go to Germany!

01:16:56.750 --> 01:16:58.125
Maybe you would be
happier there!

01:16:58.208 --> 01:16:59.917
Shame on all of you!

01:17:00.000 --> 01:17:02.166
Shame on every one of you!
You should be home right now!

01:17:02.250 --> 01:17:04.709
- He made you District
Commissioner.

01:17:04.792 --> 01:17:06.500
He's commander-in-chief
now.

01:17:06.583 --> 01:17:07.792
Commander-in-chief

01:17:07.875 --> 01:17:11.000
doesn't
get spanked by his mommy.

01:17:11.083 --> 01:17:13.792
Not with
the whole world watching.

01:17:13.875 --> 01:17:17.875
[crowd shouting]

01:17:17.959 --> 01:17:21.291
[sirens approaching]

01:17:21.375 --> 01:17:29.417
♪  ♪

01:17:32.875 --> 01:17:34.792
- Miss Alice Paul?
- I'm Lucy Burns.

01:17:34.875 --> 01:17:37.208
- I'm sorry, miss,
you're under arrest. All of you.

01:17:37.291 --> 01:17:39.000
- What? We haven't
done anything.

01:17:39.083 --> 01:17:41.417
What's the charge then?
I'm talking to you!

01:17:41.500 --> 01:17:44.458
What is it?
What's the charge?

01:17:44.542 --> 01:17:52.625
♪  ♪

01:18:06.625 --> 01:18:08.333
- They've been arrested.
Contact the families.

01:18:08.417 --> 01:18:10.917
Mabel, go down to the station.
Call me when you get there.

01:18:12.041 --> 01:18:14.375
[whistle blown]

01:18:18.667 --> 01:18:19.667
- If you want to hold them,

01:18:19.750 --> 01:18:21.625
we gotta charge them
with something.

01:18:22.583 --> 01:18:25.959
- What?
- Obstructing traffic.

01:18:28.083 --> 01:18:30.208
[gavel tapping]

01:18:35.417 --> 01:18:37.959
- These arrests
are purely political.

01:18:38.041 --> 01:18:39.625
The charge of
obstructing traffic

01:18:39.709 --> 01:18:41.917
is political subterfuge.

01:18:42.000 --> 01:18:44.125
both: We know, and I believe
the court knows

01:18:44.208 --> 01:18:46.583
that President Wilson
and his administration

01:18:46.667 --> 01:18:48.667
are responsible
for our being here today.

01:18:48.750 --> 01:18:51.333
all: We are not guilty
of any offense.

01:18:51.417 --> 01:18:54.041
I will continue to plead

01:18:54.125 --> 01:18:57.667
for the political liberty
of American women.

01:18:57.750 --> 01:18:59.208
- Where 16 of us face...

01:18:59.291 --> 01:19:00.667
- Where 10 of us
face your judgment today...

01:19:00.750 --> 01:19:03.750
- Where 12 of us face
your judgment today...

01:19:05.375 --> 01:19:08.709
- There will be 60 tomorrow.

01:19:08.792 --> 01:19:11.333
- I find these defendants
guilty as charged

01:19:11.417 --> 01:19:13.959
of obstructing traffic
in violation

01:19:14.041 --> 01:19:17.875
of the police regulations
and the act of Congress.

01:19:19.500 --> 01:19:23.250
$10 each, or 60 days
in the Occoquan Workhouse.

01:19:23.333 --> 01:19:24.417
- That's not enough!

01:19:24.500 --> 01:19:26.000
[gavel hits]

01:19:29.166 --> 01:19:32.041
- To pay the fine would be
admitting guilt.

01:19:32.125 --> 01:19:34.875
We haven't broken the law.

01:19:34.959 --> 01:19:36.625
Not one dollar.

01:19:36.709 --> 01:19:38.208
[crowd murmurs in shock]

01:19:38.291 --> 01:19:39.750
judge: 60 days in Occoquan.

01:19:39.834 --> 01:19:43.250
- What?
You can't do that!

01:19:43.333 --> 01:19:46.959
[commotion]

01:19:48.834 --> 01:19:51.208
- Should we ask for
presidential pardon?

01:19:51.291 --> 01:19:52.417
- There's nothing
to be pardoned for.

01:19:52.500 --> 01:19:53.917
The charges were false.

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:55.792
- American citizens were
arrested on a bogus charge

01:19:55.875 --> 01:19:58.625
while exercising
their constitutional right.

01:19:58.709 --> 01:20:00.000
Alice: Just get them out
on appeal.

01:20:00.083 --> 01:20:01.750
60 days for
obstructing traffic?

01:20:01.834 --> 01:20:03.166
It's gotta be coming from
the district commissioners.

01:20:03.250 --> 01:20:04.375
They're appointed
by the president.

01:20:04.458 --> 01:20:05.458
- Are we picketing tomorrow?

01:20:05.542 --> 01:20:06.458
- Yes, no mothers.

01:20:06.542 --> 01:20:07.500
[phone rings]

01:20:07.583 --> 01:20:08.792
Hold on.

01:20:08.875 --> 01:20:10.750
Is that the "Times"?
- Yeah.

01:20:10.834 --> 01:20:13.458
- Don't bury this.
What's your name?

01:20:13.542 --> 01:20:15.750
Hold on.

01:20:15.834 --> 01:20:18.500
Find a marshal
and file a--

01:20:18.583 --> 01:20:20.083
Just get them out.

01:20:20.166 --> 01:20:24.500
[overlapping chatter]

01:20:24.583 --> 01:20:25.625
What?

01:20:25.709 --> 01:20:26.959
No.

01:20:27.041 --> 01:20:28.083
O-double C-O-Q-U-A-N.

01:20:28.166 --> 01:20:30.291
It's a workhouse in Virginia.

01:20:30.375 --> 01:20:32.834
Matthew O'Brien,
he'll take the case.

01:20:35.875 --> 01:20:38.500
woman: Alice.

01:20:38.583 --> 01:20:42.458
[dramatic music]

01:20:42.542 --> 01:20:45.333
man: All right, men,
let's go.

01:20:45.417 --> 01:20:46.542
Load up!

01:20:46.625 --> 01:20:48.333
man: Yes, sir.

01:20:48.417 --> 01:20:51.208
- All right, get on board.

01:20:51.291 --> 01:20:59.417
♪  ♪

01:21:09.500 --> 01:21:11.166
- [shivers]
We're political prisoners.

01:21:11.250 --> 01:21:12.834
We wear our own clothes.

01:21:12.917 --> 01:21:15.583
- You'll wear
what they all wear.

01:21:15.667 --> 01:21:17.000
- I want to see the warden.

01:21:17.083 --> 01:21:19.583
- You want to see 'im naked?

01:21:52.750 --> 01:21:55.375
Lucy: We haven't eaten, we have
been sitting here for hours.

01:21:55.458 --> 01:21:56.583
We need food.

01:21:56.667 --> 01:21:58.375
- You'll eat when
it's time to eat.

01:21:58.458 --> 01:22:00.083
You'll bed down when
it's time to bed down.

01:22:00.166 --> 01:22:02.333
Now, you bed down.
Matron!

01:22:03.250 --> 01:22:04.667
- We are not guilty
of any crime.

01:22:04.750 --> 01:22:06.250
We're political prisoners.

01:22:06.333 --> 01:22:08.542
Now, I want these women fed
and given pen and paper

01:22:08.625 --> 01:22:10.083
to write to their families.

01:22:10.166 --> 01:22:13.458
And we want our own
clothes back, now!

01:22:13.542 --> 01:22:15.792
- Now...

01:22:15.875 --> 01:22:17.291
you bed down.

01:22:17.375 --> 01:22:18.709
- What are you--
what are you doing?

01:22:18.792 --> 01:22:20.959
Ah!
You're hurting me!

01:22:21.041 --> 01:22:24.208
[overlapping shouting]

01:22:29.125 --> 01:22:31.500
- Easy does it.

01:22:31.583 --> 01:22:39.709
♪  ♪

01:22:42.583 --> 01:22:44.583
- Mrs. Lewis!

01:22:44.667 --> 01:22:45.667
Doris!

01:22:45.750 --> 01:22:48.166
- Shut up!
Lucy: Is anybody hurt?

01:22:52.500 --> 01:22:55.709
Ruza!
Ruza, are you there?

01:22:55.792 --> 01:22:59.125
♪  ♪

01:22:59.208 --> 01:23:00.750
- Ow!

01:23:00.834 --> 01:23:03.041
Let me down!

01:23:03.125 --> 01:23:05.041
- Katherine!
Ah!

01:23:05.125 --> 01:23:08.125
man: No talking.
man: Lock down!

01:23:08.208 --> 01:23:10.500
man: Got 'em!
man: Lock it down.

01:23:14.667 --> 01:23:16.959
- If she opens
her mouth again,

01:23:17.041 --> 01:23:18.750
put a buckle gag
on her.

01:23:18.834 --> 01:23:20.291
- Yes, sir.
- Any of them!

01:23:20.375 --> 01:23:25.542
- [whimpering
in foreign language]

01:23:39.083 --> 01:23:47.250
♪  ♪

01:24:15.291 --> 01:24:16.875
- Where are the girls?

01:24:16.959 --> 01:24:20.875
- I had Mrs. Quinn
take them to my mother's.

01:24:20.959 --> 01:24:23.041
To free you up.

01:24:23.125 --> 01:24:25.000
I know how busy you are

01:24:25.083 --> 01:24:28.458
with all your
suffrage activities.

01:24:31.125 --> 01:24:35.291
People saw you, and Jenny,
at the suffrage trial.

01:24:36.500 --> 01:24:39.458
I don't know
what kind of mother

01:24:39.542 --> 01:24:42.917
takes an 11-year-old
to a district courthouse.

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:47.083
Did you give her a look
at the jail, too?

01:24:47.166 --> 01:24:49.375
- I'll go and get them
after breakfast.

01:24:49.458 --> 01:24:51.667
- No, you won't.
You leave them be.

01:24:51.750 --> 01:24:54.792
I don't know a judge
in this district

01:24:54.875 --> 01:24:57.166
who would give you
custody right now.

01:25:00.667 --> 01:25:03.667
- You won't take
my children.

01:25:03.750 --> 01:25:06.375
- How will you stop me?

01:25:06.458 --> 01:25:09.333
Can you afford an attorney?

01:25:09.417 --> 01:25:11.875
- An attorney?

01:25:11.959 --> 01:25:16.125
To prove what,
that I'm their mother?

01:25:16.208 --> 01:25:19.917
And what will your judge say,
that this is your house?

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:22.625
Your house
and your children.

01:25:22.709 --> 01:25:26.125
What am I to you, Tom,
what am I then, in your house?

01:25:26.208 --> 01:25:29.083
Chattel?
This is how you punish me?

01:25:29.166 --> 01:25:31.000
I'm their mother!

01:25:31.083 --> 01:25:34.500
They are not your
children to take!

01:25:34.583 --> 01:25:37.458
[somber music]

01:25:37.542 --> 01:25:44.291
♪ ♪

01:25:44.375 --> 01:25:45.583
[door slams]

01:25:48.208 --> 01:25:50.750
- I can't find my hat.
- Which hat?

01:25:50.834 --> 01:25:52.917
- What do you mean which hat?
My hat.

01:25:53.000 --> 01:25:54.875
- Where were you
when you took it off?

01:25:54.959 --> 01:25:56.125
- Jesus Christ, Mabel,

01:25:56.208 --> 01:25:58.667
if I'd remember
I'd know where it was.

01:26:06.500 --> 01:26:08.041
Have we heard from O'Brien?

01:26:08.125 --> 01:26:09.875
- He filed the writ.

01:26:09.959 --> 01:26:12.959
He's meeting with the judge.
He'll call us back.

01:26:13.041 --> 01:26:14.417
The Home Defense League
revoked

01:26:14.500 --> 01:26:17.500
Maud Younger's permit
to speak in Nashville.

01:26:17.583 --> 01:26:18.709
According to Senator Walsh

01:26:18.792 --> 01:26:20.625
we're called
the "iron jawed angels".

01:26:20.709 --> 01:26:22.333
Is that supposed
to be an insult?

01:26:22.417 --> 01:26:27.166
And, oh, Carrie Catt told
the "New York Times" that...

01:26:27.250 --> 01:26:31.083
we were no better than
anarchists and draft dodgers.

01:26:32.667 --> 01:26:33.750
[blows]

01:26:49.834 --> 01:26:52.792
[church bell tolls]

01:26:52.875 --> 01:26:56.291
[horse hooves clopping]

01:26:56.375 --> 01:26:57.792
[door opens]

01:27:00.291 --> 01:27:04.959
- We drew straws to see
who'd bring you dinner.

01:27:05.041 --> 01:27:06.750
I lost.

01:27:24.959 --> 01:27:26.542
- I'm not hungry.
You can have it.

01:27:26.625 --> 01:27:29.291
- Thanks.

01:27:29.375 --> 01:27:36.750
♪  ♪

01:27:36.834 --> 01:27:42.291
- How can you eat
with Doris in jail?

01:27:42.375 --> 01:27:44.000
[sighs]

01:27:45.959 --> 01:27:48.083
I can't find
a photographer to show up

01:27:48.166 --> 01:27:49.291
at the west gate tomorrow.

01:27:49.375 --> 01:27:52.208
- Call the "Post,"
talk to the news editor.

01:27:52.291 --> 01:27:56.125
- He said 326 Americans
died at a ridge.

01:27:56.208 --> 01:27:58.083
He said I wasn't
holding any cards.

01:27:58.166 --> 01:28:00.083
He said I should know
when to fold.

01:28:00.166 --> 01:28:04.375
- He doesn't know about
the ace up your sleeve.

01:28:04.458 --> 01:28:06.959
You couldn't fold
if your life depended on it.

01:28:07.041 --> 01:28:09.792
You don't know how.

01:28:09.875 --> 01:28:12.959
Don't take that
as a compliment.

01:28:13.041 --> 01:28:16.917
Look, Doris is having
the time of her life.

01:28:17.041 --> 01:28:18.250
Don't worry.

01:28:18.333 --> 01:28:21.417
She'll write
a book about it.

01:28:22.417 --> 01:28:25.667
[birds flutter]

01:28:25.750 --> 01:28:28.458
I changed my mind
about the hat.

01:28:28.542 --> 01:28:30.542
It suits you.

01:28:38.375 --> 01:28:41.542
- Ben.

01:28:41.625 --> 01:28:43.041
Ben!

01:28:57.625 --> 01:28:59.667
Mabel, how many
volunteers do we have

01:28:59.750 --> 01:29:01.291
for tomorrow's
picket line?

01:29:01.375 --> 01:29:04.208
- Uh, I have to
check my list.

01:29:04.291 --> 01:29:06.750
- Okay, well, add my name.
- No, I won't.

01:29:06.834 --> 01:29:08.542
Alice, they'll lock you up,

01:29:08.625 --> 01:29:11.333
and it won't be for
a lousy 60 days either.

01:29:11.417 --> 01:29:12.792
We need you out here.

01:29:12.875 --> 01:29:14.375
Besides, I promised
Lucy I wouldn't

01:29:14.458 --> 01:29:17.291
until we were up a creek,
dead in the water.

01:29:17.375 --> 01:29:19.792
- Mabel, add my name.

01:29:20.709 --> 01:29:22.458
♪  ♪

01:29:22.542 --> 01:29:25.000
Alice: "I believe
the might of America

01:29:25.083 --> 01:29:27.834
"is the sincere love
of its people

01:29:27.917 --> 01:29:31.166
for the freedom of mankind."

01:29:31.250 --> 01:29:37.041
Woodrow Wilson,
March 6th, 1915.

01:29:38.291 --> 01:29:40.792
"We've forgotten
the history of our country

01:29:40.875 --> 01:29:43.250
"if we have forgotten
how to agitate

01:29:43.333 --> 01:29:45.041
when it is necessary."

01:29:45.125 --> 01:29:49.166
Woodrow Wilson,
September 8, 1916.

01:29:49.250 --> 01:29:52.917
♪  ♪

01:29:53.000 --> 01:29:57.041
"Liberty is a fierce
and intractable thing

01:29:57.125 --> 01:30:00.291
to which no bounds
ought to be set."

01:30:00.375 --> 01:30:05.792
Woodrow Wilson,
a message to Congress.

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:10.750
"There is nothing in liberty

01:30:10.834 --> 01:30:16.125
unless it is translated
into definite action."

01:30:17.625 --> 01:30:22.458
July Fourth, 1914,
Woodrow Wilson.

01:30:22.542 --> 01:30:30.709
♪  ♪

01:30:43.625 --> 01:30:50.250
♪  ♪

01:30:50.333 --> 01:30:53.458
[all shouting]

01:31:10.500 --> 01:31:13.458
Alice: I don't wish to make
any plea before this court.

01:31:13.542 --> 01:31:15.583
I have nothing to do with
the making of the laws

01:31:15.667 --> 01:31:17.291
which have put me
in this position.

01:31:17.375 --> 01:31:20.959
I am not here because
I obstructed traffic,

01:31:21.041 --> 01:31:23.291
but because I pointed out
to President Wilson

01:31:23.375 --> 01:31:26.542
that he is obstructing
democracy.

01:31:26.625 --> 01:31:28.375
- Refused?

01:31:28.458 --> 01:31:29.709
What do you mean?

01:31:29.792 --> 01:31:32.125
- Mrs. Leighton
made it very clear

01:31:32.208 --> 01:31:34.375
I wasn't her attorney.

01:31:34.458 --> 01:31:35.709
And she instructed the court

01:31:35.792 --> 01:31:38.500
not to accept bail
or fees on her behalf.

01:31:38.583 --> 01:31:41.583
And she gave a statement
to a reporter.

01:31:41.667 --> 01:31:44.208
She said that,
in prison or out

01:31:44.291 --> 01:31:46.875
American women are not free.

01:31:49.917 --> 01:31:52.875
[machines clattering]

01:31:58.417 --> 01:32:01.458
[women murmur excitedly]

01:32:03.667 --> 01:32:06.041
- No talking!

01:32:11.500 --> 01:32:15.166
- It's warm in here.
Can we open a window?

01:32:15.250 --> 01:32:17.041
- Get to work.

01:32:18.583 --> 01:32:21.458
- Can't you see
she looks faint?

01:32:21.542 --> 01:32:26.291
I'm only asking
that you open a window.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:30.625
- Uh, matron.

01:32:30.709 --> 01:32:32.959
My needle broke.
May I have another?

01:32:41.834 --> 01:32:44.208
[screams and gasps]

01:32:44.291 --> 01:32:46.000
- That's better, isn't it?

01:32:46.083 --> 01:32:48.709
- Put her in solitary!

01:32:48.792 --> 01:32:51.083
[all banging tables in unison]

01:32:51.166 --> 01:32:53.375
You...

01:32:53.458 --> 01:32:56.333
clean that up.

01:33:20.375 --> 01:33:22.291
[clattering]

01:33:24.333 --> 01:33:29.917
♪  ♪

01:33:30.000 --> 01:33:32.125
I'll have to report this
to the warden.

01:33:32.208 --> 01:33:36.166
- I'm entitled to clean water
and an empty slop bucket.

01:33:49.500 --> 01:33:52.667
[door closes]

01:33:58.041 --> 01:34:01.041
- I'm a lawyer,
not a magician, Miss Vernon.

01:34:01.125 --> 01:34:03.625
Whitaker says no one
in solitary can see counsel,

01:34:03.709 --> 01:34:05.291
no one sees counsel.

01:34:05.375 --> 01:34:07.542
It's a new prison, the jerks
got the run of the place

01:34:07.625 --> 01:34:09.291
until they got their
paperwork in order.

01:34:09.375 --> 01:34:11.417
I need a judge
who's not on a string.

01:34:20.000 --> 01:34:23.333
- We can't have a martyr
on our heads.

01:34:23.417 --> 01:34:25.375
♪  ♪

01:34:25.458 --> 01:34:28.417
- Get on your feet!

01:34:28.500 --> 01:34:32.000
- What are you doing?

01:34:32.083 --> 01:34:34.083
- Okay.

01:34:45.917 --> 01:34:48.500
man: I'm Dr. White, Alice.

01:34:48.583 --> 01:34:52.041
The district commissioner
asked me to speak with you.

01:34:56.125 --> 01:34:58.792
Do you know where you are?

01:34:58.875 --> 01:35:02.583
- District Prison Hospital.

01:35:02.667 --> 01:35:03.667
The mental ward.

01:35:03.750 --> 01:35:06.166
- You refuse to eat.

01:35:06.250 --> 01:35:08.417
Can you tell me why?

01:35:10.166 --> 01:35:13.625
- The hunger strike was
a tradition in old Ireland.

01:35:13.709 --> 01:35:16.500
You starve yourself
on someone's doorstep

01:35:16.583 --> 01:35:19.542
until restitution is made

01:35:19.625 --> 01:35:21.625
and justice is done.

01:35:21.709 --> 01:35:24.166
- It doesn't sound like
a very effective method.

01:35:24.250 --> 01:35:28.208
- A stinking corpse
on your doorstep?

01:35:28.291 --> 01:35:30.000
What will the neighbors say?

01:35:30.083 --> 01:35:33.875
- So you stand on
the president's doorstep.

01:35:33.959 --> 01:35:37.041
He's treated you
very badly, hasn't he?

01:35:37.125 --> 01:35:39.375
- It's the law
that treats women badly.

01:35:39.458 --> 01:35:41.208
- But you picket
President Wilson.

01:35:41.291 --> 01:35:43.750
He's the one
who put you here.

01:35:48.792 --> 01:35:53.083
- We picket the office
of the presidency.

01:35:53.166 --> 01:35:55.709
It has nothing to do
with Mr. Wilson

01:35:55.792 --> 01:35:58.375
and everything to do with
the position he holds.

01:35:58.458 --> 01:36:02.542
- But, he's responsible
for your treatment here.

01:36:05.083 --> 01:36:08.875
- I believe I was sent here
by a district commissioner.

01:36:10.834 --> 01:36:13.125
- You call yourself
a suffragist.

01:36:19.291 --> 01:36:20.834
- Yes.

01:36:23.500 --> 01:36:26.417
- Tell me about your cause.

01:36:26.500 --> 01:36:29.917
Just...talk freely.

01:36:30.000 --> 01:36:32.333
Explain yourself.

01:36:35.709 --> 01:36:39.917
Do you understand
the question?

01:36:40.000 --> 01:36:42.875
- You asked me
to explain myself.

01:36:45.875 --> 01:36:49.750
I just wonder what
needs to be explained.

01:36:49.834 --> 01:36:52.709
It should be very clear.

01:36:57.792 --> 01:37:01.750
Look into your own heart.

01:37:01.834 --> 01:37:05.750
I swear to you,
mine's no different.

01:37:09.000 --> 01:37:11.750
You want a place in
the trades and professions

01:37:11.834 --> 01:37:14.625
where you can earn your bread.

01:37:14.709 --> 01:37:17.166
So do I.

01:37:17.250 --> 01:37:21.500
You want some means
of self-expression,

01:37:21.583 --> 01:37:27.250
some way of satisfying
your own personal ambitions.

01:37:27.333 --> 01:37:28.917
So do I.

01:37:30.291 --> 01:37:35.709
Want a voice in the government
under which you live.

01:37:35.792 --> 01:37:37.792
So do I.

01:37:39.083 --> 01:37:41.917
What is there to explain?

01:38:04.000 --> 01:38:08.959
- She shows no signs of
persecution mania or delusion.

01:38:09.041 --> 01:38:11.291
I concur with Dr. Hickling.

01:38:11.375 --> 01:38:14.041
There is no medical
basis for a diagnosis.

01:38:14.125 --> 01:38:16.542
- You don't feel she needs to be
permanently hospitalized?

01:38:16.625 --> 01:38:19.333
- For her own safety.
She's suicidal.

01:38:19.417 --> 01:38:22.125
You said so in your report.
The prison doctor said so.

01:38:22.208 --> 01:38:24.583
- I said she was prepared
to starve to death

01:38:24.667 --> 01:38:26.625
in order to
further her cause.

01:38:26.709 --> 01:38:28.792
- Well, okay,
I'm not a doc

01:38:28.875 --> 01:38:30.750
but that sure sounds
unhealthy to me.

01:38:30.834 --> 01:38:33.709
- "Give me liberty
or give me death."

01:38:33.792 --> 01:38:35.875
Patrick Henry,
an American hero.

01:38:35.959 --> 01:38:37.667
- Apples and oranges.

01:38:37.750 --> 01:38:39.709
- In oranges and women

01:38:39.792 --> 01:38:43.208
courage is often
mistaken for insanity.

01:39:13.959 --> 01:39:15.542
- Eyes front!

01:39:15.625 --> 01:39:18.166
Eyes front!

01:39:41.542 --> 01:39:44.166
- Hunger strike.

01:39:52.917 --> 01:39:56.291
- ♪ I was standing ♪

01:39:56.375 --> 01:40:00.166
♪ By my window ♪

01:40:00.250 --> 01:40:02.041
♪ On a cold ♪

01:40:02.125 --> 01:40:06.291
both: ♪ And cloudy day ♪

01:40:06.375 --> 01:40:07.709
- Quiet!

01:40:07.792 --> 01:40:11.166
all: ♪ When I saw that ♪

01:40:11.250 --> 01:40:15.041
♪ Hearse come rolling ♪

01:40:15.125 --> 01:40:17.083
♪ For to carry ♪

01:40:17.166 --> 01:40:21.792
♪ My mother away ♪

01:40:21.875 --> 01:40:25.500
